<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Double Funds for Romania Starting 2000: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Romania's progress in
macrostability and the economic reform are mandatory processes,
which will contribute to the improvement of its image on external
markets and will ease its access to the capital market, visiting
EU officials said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Giovanni Ravasio, head of the EU General Directorate for
economic and financial relations and coordinator of the
macro-financial assistance for the candidate countries,
underscored that these processes prompted the mobilization of
important EU funds.
</P>
<P>
Francois Lamoureux, the head of the General Directorate for
relations with the Central and East European countries and
coordinator of the EU enlargement process said that starting the
year 2000, the EU would double its funds for Romania, reaching 350
million Euro.
</P>
<P>
No other East-European county, with the exception of Romania,
receives such funds, the EU official said, adding that they want
to be sure that the funds ''will be used function of a series of
priorities of the Executive, that are clear and precise''.
</P>
<P>
With reference to the loan the EU will give Romania for
balancing its trade, Ravasio announced that there already was a
principle agreement in this respect and the negotiations were on
track and were to be followed by the signing of a Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Romania will be able to use all the money it will
receive from the EU, Lamoureaux said he hoped it would be able to
take in the money and stressed that the funds should not exceed 4
percent of Romania's GDP.
</P>
<P>
The EU officials are in Romania to finalize the EU's strategy
of support to the Romanian Government regarding the economic
reform and to hold talks on the process of Romania's admission to
the EU, with a look to the Helsinki summit of next December.
</P>
</TEXT>
