<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Pledges Reform in Civil Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
Monday pledged to "modernize" the country's archaic public service
through a program of staff re-orientation, pay increment and law
reform.
</P>
<P>
Already, two pillars of the service, the civil service rules
and financial regulation were being updated to make them
consistent with modern management practise, Obasanjo said during
an unscheduled meeting with civil servants in capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo repeated a campaign promise to pay "adequate
remuneration" for the country's 600,000-strong public servants,
whose size had been cut by the last military regime to promote
efficiency and reduce recurrent expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The reduction came after the government had agreed on a pay
rise with the umbrella trade union for public sector workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
