<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt. Urges to Reopen Closed Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- All mines which closed in the past
should consider reopening again to generate more employment,
Zimbabwean Minister of Mines, Environment and Tourism Simon Moyo
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said the government is making efforts to revisit every
mine, which was closed in the past because of financial problems,
to find ways of resuscitating those to reemploy hundreds of people
who lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the official opening of a three-day seminar, the
minister said that mining is an essential sector of the economy
which contributed about seven percent to the growth domestic
product (GDP) and 35 percent to net foreign currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
"The main commodities being sought after are diamonds, gold,
platinum group metals, copper and nickel," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government recognized the role played by
small- and medium-scale mining in job creation and rural
development.
</P>
<P>
The mining industry employs about 40,000 people. Despite the
current low prices of minerals, Zimbabwe has more than 290
exclusive prospecting orders compared with 238 at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The seminar organized by the Mine Workers Association is being
attended by about 50 representatives from different mines
throughout the southern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
