<HEADLINE> Demining Activities Paralyzed in Angola: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Due to renewed civil war, the
demining activities have paralyzed across Angola, a senior Angolan
official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Helder Cruz, Director of the National Bureau for Removing
Obstacles and Explosives, told Xinhua that the 19 demining teams
of the government have shrunk into five as a result of the fierce
fighting and the lack of financial support.
</P>
<P>
The remaining five teams can only afford to advertising the
harm of the land mines, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The demining projects have all come to a halt while most of the
foreign experts in the bureau have returned home, Cruz said,
adding that even over half of the Angolan personnel in his bureau
left.
</P>
<P>
The director noted that the demining teams, sponsored by
foreign governments or non-governmental organizations, have moved
to other countries such as Mozambique and Cambodia due to
insecurity in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Cruz said that there are 370 to 400 cases of land mine
explosion in Angola each year, causing a lot of casualties.
</P>
<P>
As the war has escalated and the rebels of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have planted more
land mines, the causalities will increase, the director pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of the countries which have numerous land mines.
 According to statistics released by the United Nations, more than
11 million land mines had been planted in the war-torn country
over the past three decades, posing great danger to the life of
Angolans and the economy there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
