<HEADLINE> French ``Prince'' in Nigeria Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- ``Chief Jean,'' a Frenchman from
Marseille who was proclaimed in 1997 a ``prince'' of Nigeria by
the king of Ibeju, a small kingdom of Yorouba in southwest
Nigeria, has died of a heart attack at the age of 56, said Agence
France-Presse on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jean Sicard, who owned an export company of primary materials
for industry, settled in Nigeria at the age of 12 and was a VIP of
the French community in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
When he was proclaimed prince of Obumba Amuludun -- meaning
``the right arm of the king and maker of good deeds'' -- of
Iberekodo by King Musa Agbabiaka II of Ibeju two years ago, many
diplomatic personalities attended the ceremony, covered by French
television.
</P>
<P>
Sicard, who was also a vertern amateur actress in Lagos, won
the respect of the inhabitants of the village of Iberekodo at the
Atlantic coast, becoming the first white man to be honored with
the title of prince there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
