<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-31 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, India Sign Cooperation Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and India on Monday signed an
agreement on economic and oil cooperation, the Iraqi News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid
and his Indian counterpart K. Ramamurthy who arrived here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said in a statement that the two countries agreed to
strengthen cooperation in the fields of industry, oil, agriculture
and trade.
</P>
<P>
Terming the signing of the agreement as a significant step
toward more cooperation between Iraq and India, Rashid said that
Indian companies would work together with their Iraqi partners to
modernize Iraq's oil industry, especially in the oil refinery
sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Iraq will meet a large percentage of
India's needs for crude oil under the framework of the current
sixth phase of the U.N. oil-for-food program, and will meet all
India's needs for oil in the future.
</P>
<P>
The sixth phase of the oil-for-food deal, which took effect
last week, allows Iraq to export 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth
of oil in six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and India agreed that the forthcoming session of the
Iraqi-Indian joint committee for economic, trade cooperation will
be held in Baghdad in July, said Rashid.
</P>
<P>
He added that Indian companies will participate in the
oil-for-food program to meet the needs of Iraqi oil sector for
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Ramamurthy said that his meeting with President
Saddam Hussein is an important step that will actively raise the
level of relations between the two countries, adding that his
visit to Iraq has brought about positive results.
</P>
<P>
The Indian minister stressed that his country will continue to
contact with Iraq to implement Iraq's oil projects and to train
Iraq's oil staff in India, saying that his country is determined
to sign long-term contracts with Iraq in this regard.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Saddam and Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan
met with Ramamurthy respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
