<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Criticizes Rich Countries' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Rich countries are imposing policies
that shattered natural resources management in developing
countries, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said in Harare
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The policies have made our natural resources excessively cheap
while limiting our ability to export value-added natural
resources," he said when opening a National Environment
Conservation Conference to debate issues affecting people in the
areas of environment and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
He noted that rich countries are destroying the environment
management programs through mean aid programs, economic policies
and attitudes.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the policies have resulted in
developing countries trapped in indebtedness, excessive resource
extractions and perpetual exportation of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also said there was need to review environment
legislation in Zimbabwe to conform with requirements of
sustainable utilization of resources.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day conference organized by the Natural Resources
Board, over 500 delegates would examine the implications of the
country's Environment Management Bill.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said his government is confident the bill would lead to
sustainable management of the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
