<HEADLINE> More U.S.-British Air Violations Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British warplanes on
Monday continued to violate Iraqi airspace in the north and south
of the country, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:42 (0642 GMT) 23 formations of
enemy warplanes from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated southern
Iraqi airspace over Basra, Thi-Qar, Qadisiya, Misan and Muthana
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi anti-aircraft units repulsed the enemy planes at
14:00 (1000 GMT), the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Eleven formations of enemy warplanes coming from the Turkish
airspace violated northern Iraqi airspace over Neineva, Dohuk and
Erbil provinces at 10:25 (0625 GMT), said the spokesman, adding
that Iraqi air defenses repelled the enemy planes at 14:10 (1010
GMT).
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S. and British bombardment of Iraq,
their warplanes have made 5,775 sorties in the south and 1,457
sorties in the north of the country, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched four-night airstrikes against
Iraq in mid-December last year to retaliate what they called
Iraq's failure to fully cooperate with U.N. arms inspectors in
charge of eliminating Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
Since last December, the U.S. and British warplanes have been
regularly attacking Iraqi military and civilian targets in these
restricted zones, causing severe civilian casualties and property
damages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
