<HEADLINE> Sub-Saharan Africa Urged To Improve Reproductive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The sub-Saharan African countries
need to allocate more financial and human resources to maintain
and sustain efforts of improving reproductive health services,
Zimbabwe's Health and Child Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Stamps said this at the official opening of a two-week regional
project development workshop aimed at fostering the south-south
collaboration in reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
The countries should come up with their own project proposals
on how to improve reproductive health, said the health minister.
</P>
<P>
He also called on civil society and the private sector to take
a lead in supporting the advancement of reproductive health
services.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan African regional director for reproductive health
Josephine Moyo said that it is important for countries in the
region to cooperate in the field of reproductive health and not to
depend on donor support.
</P>
<P>
"What we need is to promote resources which are available in
the region," the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Moyo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is attended by 40 experts and officials from
Zimbabwe, Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
It is aimed at identifying and mobilizing financial and
technical resources for the South-South collaboration activities
in developing project proposals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
