<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Georgia to Sign 10 Cooperation Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Georgia will sign several
agreements on economic cooperation during a visit by the Georgian
foreign minister this week, an Egyptian official announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Foreign Minister Mohamed Fathi al-Shazli told
reporters that Georgian Foreign Minister Irakli Menagharishvili is
scheduled to arrive in Cairo on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit, Menagharishvili will hold talks
with his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa on regional issues of
mutual concern, including the latest developments in Caucasia and
the Middle East, and ways of promoting bilateral relations,
al-Shazli said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two countries will sign 10 agreements in the
fields of trade, investment protection and cooperation in the
economic, scientific and technical domains.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of Egypt's Fund for Technical Cooperation
with the Commonwealth of the Independent States Ashraf Zaazaa said
in the day that the fund has offered 236 training courses to
Georgia in various specializations.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 more training courses will be granted to Georgia by the
end of this year, Zaazaa said, adding that the fund has dispatched
experts to the country in the fields of history, protocol,
diplomacy and science.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would meet with the Georgian foreign minister
for talks on means of upgrading bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a source at Georgia's Embassy in Cairo told Egypt's
Middle East News Agency that Menagharishvili will deliver a
message to President Hosni Mubarak from his Georgian counterpart
Eduard Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
The source said that Menagharishvili will also meet with
Speaker of the Egyptian People's Assembly (Parliament) and
officials of the Arab League. 
</P>
</TEXT>
