<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Regrets IRA Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's Sinn Fein
President Gerry Adams expressed his "regret" on Monday at the
deaths of eight IRA victims who went missing in the 1970s and
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
But he said it was just one of the "injustices" which sprung
from the Troubles.
</P>
<P>
Adams was speaking on BBC Radio 4's Today program as police in
the Irish Republic resumed their search for the remains of IRA
victims.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional IRA has supplied details through intermediaries
of the locations of eight victims -- all but one of whom were
Roman Catholics who went missing from Northern Ireland between
1972 and 1981.
</P>
<P>
The paramilitaries have named seven sites south of the border
and on Friday police discovered a body, believed to be that of
Eamon Molloy, at one of those -- a graveyard at Faughart in County
Louth.
</P>
<P>
Adams said: "These things happen in war...in war horrible
things are done and there can be no attempt by me to minimise that
or in any way diminish the responsibility of republicans."
</P>
<P>
Police began digging at three of the other six sites on Monday
morning. They are hopeful of finding remains at Carlingford,
County Louth, Culloville, County Monaghan and Ballynulty, County
Wicklow.
</P>
<P>
Officers leading the operation have acknowledged they are
relying on the memories of IRA personnel about events dating back
more than a quarter of a century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
