<HEADLINE> Rally in Zambia Marking World No-Tobacco Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is drawing up a national
action plan against tobacco and has started collaboration with the
World Health Organization (WHO) in promoting smoking cessation.
</P>
<P>
Gavin Silwemba, Deputy Director-General of Zambia Central Board
of Health, said this on Monday at a rally marking the World
No-Tobacco Day.
</P>
<P>
WHO representative in Zambia Edward Maganu said at the rally
that there is a lower number of smokers in Africa, and Zambia in
particular, compared with other regions.
</P>
<P>
However, the WHO official noted that the number of African
smokers should be reduced further by preventing tobacco use in
children and adolescents, reducing family exposure to tobacco and
providing treatment medications.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to a time when tobacco smoking in
public and work places will be a thing of the past," he said.
</P>
