<HEADLINE> Environment Worsening in Zimbabwe: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A recent research has revealed that
the the environment situation in Zimbabwe is worsening, Permanent
Secretary of the Zimbabwean Ministry of Mines, Environment and
Tourism, Charles Chipato said in Harare Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chipato told the National Conference on Environmental
Management and Natural Resources Conservation that since the first
report on the country's environment was released in 1992, Zimbabwe
has had to grapple with increasing environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
"The worsening economic and ecological environment have caught
the majority of the people in a vicious circle," said the
permanent secretary.
</P>
<P>
"An increasing population surviving on reduced natural
resources has caused growing conflict over access to resources,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"An unfriendly economic environment characterized by falling
investment, dis-investment and job loses forces people to
over-exploit natural resources," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chipato said his ministry had developed a National Biodiversity
Strategy and action plan which would seek to enable the government
to identify priority areas and actions which should be taken to
conserve and utilize biological heritage sustainably.
</P>
<P>
The government had also established a national action plan
under the desertification convention, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
