<HEADLINE> Nigerian President to Review Documents Signed by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's new President Olusegun
Obasanjo Monday suspended and put to review of all the contracts
and appointments signed by the former administration between
January 1 and May 29 this year.
</P>
<P>
A panel to be established will review the affected "contracts,
licenses, awards, approvals and appointments" signed during the
period, according to a press release issued by Doyin Okupe,
Special Assistant in charge of media and publicity to the
president.
</P>
<P>
The panel is to review the above documents or orders in light
of the country's "current economic and political realities," said
the press release.
</P>
<P>
After the review, reconfirmation, cost adjustments, or outright
 cancellation will be carried out where necessary, it said.
</P>
<P>
The press release added that the panel is expected to work with
maximum dispatch and the government's decisions on its periodic
reports will be made public.
</P>
<P>
The new president ordered that henceforth Nigerian embassies
abroad must ensure that the processing of all visa applications be
completed within 72 hours of their submission.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said the order was made because of the continued
complaints of the undue delays in granting visas by the Nigeria's
embassies, according to the press release.
</P>
<P>
The president was quoted as saying that the timely issuance of
visas to deserving applicants is very important for the inflow of
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The president, sworn in just two days ago, has pledged a quick
change to corruption and economic downturn in the most populous
African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
