<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Launches Livestock Development Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia Monday launched a
national livestock development project to enhance food security,
reduce poverty and increase the country's foreign exchange
earnings.
</P>
<P>
The five-year project, which includes livestock production,
animal health, forage production and project management, will be
implemented in all regions in the Horn of African country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of a five-day launching workshop,
Ethiopian acting minister of Agriculture, Mengistu Huluka, said
despite rich resources, the livestock sub-sector provides the
lowest per capita output of livestock products compared with other
African countries.
</P>
<P>
"Output from the livestock industry has not been accommodating
all the need of the rapidly increasing population of the country,"
the acting minister was quoted by the Ethiopian News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The acting minister attributed the low level of production to
poor genetic potential of the national herd, poor nutrition,
disease-based stresses, unsatisfactory management and absence of
appropriate market structures.
</P>
<P>
He said that "under such conditions it became impossible to
fulfil the minimum requirements of consumers, let alone catering
the need of the agro- industries."
</P>
<P>
The African Development Bank and the Ethiopian government will
finance the 39 million U.S. dollars project.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion, the project is expected to produce 288,000
tons of milk, 43,400 tons of beef and mutton, as well as 511,000
tons of fodder products annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
