<HEADLINE> Russia Steps Up Efforts on Yugoslav Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin talked over the phone with U.S. President Bill Clinton
Russia stepped up its efforts to find a political solution to the
Yugoslav crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Stepashin-Clinton telephone conversation went ahead
according to prior arrangement between Clinton and Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, the government information department
said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow provided no detail on the conversation except noting
that both sides agreed to maintain active dialogue toward
broadening bilateral ties and cooperation in the international
arena, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Stepashin and Yeltsin's envoy for Yugoslavia Viktor
Chernomyrdin met again Monday to discuss Moscow's moves on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, who is scheduled to fly to Bonn Tuesday to meet
with envoys of the United States and the European Union, also held
talks with Eduard Kukan, the Slovak foreign minister now serving
as U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's envoy for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting between German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, Russian presidential envoy for
Yugoslavia Viktor Chernomyrdin, and U.S.Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott Tuesday in Bonn has acquired particular
importance," the Russian government's information department said.
</P>
<P>
After the Bonn meeting, Chernomyrdin is expected to fly to
Belgrade, possibly together with Ahtisaari, to meet Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a ranking Russian official reiterated
Monday that if NATO continues its military operations, especially
if it launches a ground phase, if the U.S. side shows no interest
in a peaceful solution of the Kosovo problem, "a negative process
that would be very difficult to reverse could begin" in
Russian-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia, which started on March
24, has entered its 69th day Monday and resulted in the death of
over 1,500 innocent civilians and the destruction of much of the
Balkan country's industrial infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Russian Security Council deputy secretary Valentin Sobolev,
following a meeting with the U.S. Aspen strategic group, said NATO
operations against Yugoslavia are violating all international law
norms.
</P>
<P>
They have harmed and continue to seriously harm
Russian-American relations, and undermine stability in Europe and
the whole world, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
