<HEADLINE> Prisoners, Overseas Citizen Not to Vote in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Malawian Electoral Commission
said Monday that prisoners and citizens living abroad will not
vote in the forthcoming parliamentary and presidential elections
slated for June 15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the commission Justice Hames Kalaile said this when
responding to a question from journalists whether prisoners will
be able to vote on the polling day, the Malawi News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"We acknowledge that prisoners have a right to vote but, as for
1999 elections, they will not vote since the necessary
arrangements for them have not been put in place," Kalaile was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the only group which has been left out. Malawians
who are resident abroad would not be able to vote," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he added that "we must consider making provisions for them
to vote in future elections."
</P>
<P>
He said the prisoners could have voted if prison authorities
had made arrangements on how to move the prisoners to the polling
centers.
</P>
<P>
As regards the aged and blind who may not be able to make any
mark on the ballot paper, Kalaile advised that they should bring
with them a person they trust to help them vote properly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
