<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Still Waiting for Indian Response on Talks Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has not as yet received
any official communication from India on its offer for talks to
defuse tension at the Line of Control (LoC) in Kashmir, Foreign
Office spokesman Tariq Altaf said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen media reports that India has accepted the offer
but there has not been any official communication from India in
this regard, so far," Altaf told a press briefing here on the
situation at LoC.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif proposed in a telephone talk with
his Indian counterpart Atal Behari Vajpayee last Friday to send
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz to New Delhi to find ways and means
to defuse the latest tension on the LoC which, Pakistan said, has
been escalated by Indian air strikes and violations of LoC.
</P>
<P>
To a question about the Indian deployment of Mirage-2000 jets
in India-administered Kashmir, the spokesman said that Pakistan on
Monday expressed deep concern over the reported deployment of the
Mirage-2000 fighters for air strikes against "Kashmiri Mujahideen
(holy fighters)."
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely regrettable that India has brought in such
sophisticated weapons, it is unprecedented and absolutely
unacceptable," Altaf said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman said that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has held telephone conversation with Prime
Minister Sharif on the situation in Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Albright talked to Sharif last night, Altaf said. However, he
did not give details of the conversation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
