<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Contribute Up to 7,000 Soldiers to Kosovo Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- France could contribute from 6,000 to
7,000 soldiers to the future international peace force in Kosovo
(KFOR) after a ceasefire agreement is reached between NATO and
Yugoslavia, said a top French military officer on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The chief of general staff of the French armed forces, General
Jean-Pierre Kelche, said in a television interview that if
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic decides to withdraw his
troops from Kosovo, NATO will not ``crush'' the entire Yugoslav
forces if they leave.
</P>
<P>
But he also said that the announcement by Milosevic that he
will accept the principles of the Group of Eight for solving the
Kosovo conflict, which includes a withdrawal of Serbian forces
from Kosovo, should be confirmed by concrete action.
</P>
<P>
Kelche said that whatever happens in the coming days or weeks,
NATO will not be able to re-settle all the Kosovar refugees in
their homes before the arrival of winter.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that France, which is contributing to 10
percent of the NATO air force in its air campaign against
Yugoslavia, has so far completed 20 percent of the missions of
reconnaissance of the ``Allied Force'' operation over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the French aircraft carrier Foch, which will leave
Monday evening Adriatic Sea to return to its base in Toulon, will
be replaced by a frigate which is on its way to the combat zone.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of Foch means that France will reduce by one
fourth the number of its warplanes participating in the NATO air
campaign.
</P>
<P>
But France is ready to respond to supplementary demands by the
Supreme Commander of NATO in Europe, Wesley Clark, especially on
participation in attacks on ground targets, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
