<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judgment Reserved in Case of S. Africa's Botha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Cape High Court
Monday reserved judgment in the appeal by former state president
P.W. Botha against his conviction for snubbing the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC).
</P>
<P>
As the hearing drew to an end Monday, two judges heard attorney
for the state, Bruce Morrison, describe Botha as an "extremely
stubborn man who saw fit to call the TRC a circus," South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Morrison said Botha had initially appeared willing to testify
before the TRC, on condition the impression was sent out to the
world that he was appearing before an inquiry and not before a
tribunal hearing as such.
</P>
<P>
"He would have testified had he been able to do so in such a
manner that saved face," Morrison contended.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was launched before judges Selwyn Selikowitz and
John Foxcroft by Botha's legal team, comprising Lapa Laubscher and
Ernst Penzhorn.
</P>
<P>
Laubscher described Botha's sentence -- 10,000 rand (1,600 U.S.
dollars) or 12 months in prison, plus 12 months conditionally
suspended for five years -- as "shockingly inappropriate".
</P>
<P>
He compared it with a 50-rand (eight dollars) fine or 30 days
sentence imposed 24 years ago on an offender who had refused to
take the oath or answer questions before a commission of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
However, Morrison countered that the sentence imposed on Botha
was fair, considering his attitude to the TRC and the fact that he
had stultified it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25,000 S. Africans Die of Smoking Per Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A total of 25,000 South
Africans die of tobacco-related illnesses every year, the Health
Department said Monday, the World No-Tobacco Day.
</P>
<P>
The department said in a statement that smokers lose an average
of 12 years of their lives in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by the Human Sciences Research Council and the
Medical Research Council indicates that 25 percent of South
Africans smoke, while the habit is growing among children at an
alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
"The harmful effects of cigarette smoke on the health of
non-smokers are of serious concern, and public smoking further
encourages this," said the health department.
</P>
<P>
Legislation was approved earlier this year to restrict smoking
in public places, to prohibit tobacco advertising and
sponsorships, and to prevent children younger than 16 years from
buying cigarettes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
