<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rhinos Endangered in Tanzanian Game Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Rhinos are the most
endangered species in southern Tanzania's Selous Game Reserve,
Africa's largest protected area, a wildlife expert observed in Dar
es Salaam Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ludwig Siege, a senior management official of the game reserve,
said that the current number of rhinos in Selous is between 100 to
200, with a slow reproduction of these animals.
</P>
<P>
"Rhinos are the most endangered species in the reserve,
especially in the past decades," Siege said, adding that all
measures have been taken to protect the remaining rhinos.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted in 1976 in Selous Reserve showed that there
were more than 3,000 of rhinos, but the number dwindled due to
poaching especially in early 1980s, said Siege.
</P>
<P>
However, he said it is encouraging to note that Selous is rich
in wild dogs which have not been infected with the distemper
disease because of their rare or none contact with the domestic
dogs.
</P>
<P>
In Serengeti, a national park in northern Tanzania, wild dogs
are being attacked by the disease due to their connection with the
domesticated dogs in the buffer zone, he said.
</P>
<P>
Selous Game Reserve has been designated a "world heritage site"
by the United Nations due to its unique ecological importance.
</P>
<P>
The German Agency of Technical Cooperation has set aside 515
million shillings (about 725,000 U.S. dollars) in support of
Selous and other two game reserves in Tanzania for the year 1999,
to help them set up wildlife management schemes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
