<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Puppet Troupe Visits Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Chengdu Puppet Theatre's
first show in Zambian capital Lusaka Monday night was highly
appreciated and warmly acclaimed by more than 500 Zambian people.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time for a Chinese puppet theatre to perform
in Africa since it was set up in 1951. The puppeteers are
bringing eight shows to the Zambian people.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the theatre, Tang Dayu, told Xinhua that puppet shows
have a history of some 2000 years.
</P>
<P>
The art form is categorized into four types based on the shapes
of the puppets and the operative skills. There are figure
puppets, marionettes, stick puppets and wire supported puppets.
Each has got its own artistic characteristics.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, such puppet shows are usually accompanied by the
tunes of local operas and some adopt the form of dialog or
singing.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of 1970s, the theatre has hosted visiting artists
from Russia, Germany, Korea, Japan, Poland, and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The theatre will also visit Zimbabwe, Kenya, Rwanda, Ethiopia
and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's NNP Rules Out Provincial Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The New National Party (NNP)
has ruled out a coalition with the African National Congress (ANC)
in the Western Cape after South Africa's general election on June
2.
</P>
<P>
Should there be a coalition, the first choice of the NNP would
be one or more of the other opposition parties, South African
Press Association (SAPA) quoted NNP leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk
as saying in Cape Town Monday.
</P>
<P>
The NNP leader said his party is going "full-out" to win the
province on its own.
</P>
<P>
The party currently rules the province, but according to
opinion polls, the two parties are heading for a photo finish.
</P>
<P>
The opinion polls indicate that neither party will get an
absolute majority and a coalition provincial government appears to
be likely.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted Richard Calland, a senior political analyst with
the Institute for Democracy in South Africa (Idasa), as saying
Monday that he believed an ANC-NNP coalition in the Western Cape
was the most likely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
