<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain on Tuesday took a cautious stand over
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's apparent acceptance of a
Group of Eight peace plan and insisted that NATO must lead any
peacekeeping force for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"It remains to be seen what he's actually accepted," Defense
Secretary George Robertson said in an interview to the Sky
television.
</P>
<P>
"We've made it absolutely clear that our bottom line is that
all Serb troops will leave Kosovo and that there will be an
international security force with NATO at its core," he said.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made as Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
the European Union's Balkans envoy, was due to meet his Russian
counterpart Viktor Chernomyrdin and U.S. diplomat Strobe Talbott
in Bonn on Tuesday for talks on the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
After meeting in Bonn, Ahtisaari and Chernomyrdin were then due
to fly into Belgrade on Wednesday to meet Milosevic, who the
Yugoslav official Tanjug news agency said had accepted in
principle the G-8 peace plan. (Britain-NATO-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The Afghan Taliban militia Tuesday told visiting
Uzbek Foreign Minister Abdulaziz Kamilov that they would not
attend the proposed meeting of the "Six Plus Two" if invited as a
group.
</P>
<P>
Afghan sources here told Xinhua that Kamilov, who arrived here
Monday on a two-day visit, went to the southern Afghan city of
Kandahar Tuesday morning and held a meeting with Taliban supreme
leader Mulla Omar.
</P>
<P>
Kamilov was told that the Taliban would send a delegation to
the proposed meeting of "Six Plus Two" in Tashkent only if they
are invited as a "government," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Uzbek foreign minister flew into the Taliban stronghold of
Kandahar Tuesday morning and held wide-ranging talks with Omar and
other senior Taliban leaders, focusing on the Afghan turmoil.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the "Six Plus Two" group at deputy foreign
minister-level is proposed in Tashkent with expected participation
of Afghan factions. However, the date for the meeting has yet to
be announced. (Afghanistan-Taliban-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The Yugoslav government has in principle accepted the
cease-fire terms set by the Group of Eight to solve the Kosovo
crisis, a German Foreign Ministry spokesman confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest position of Belgrade was made clear in a letter sent
by Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic to his German
counterpart Joscher whose country holds the rotating presidency of
the EU. The content of the letter was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
However, Jovanovic affirmed in the letter that Yugoslavia
accepted the principles worked out by the seven most
industrialized nations and Russia for the settlement of the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
These terms include the withdrawal of the Yugoslav government
forces and paramilitary units from Kosovo, a deployment of U.N.-
authorized international troops, the return of Kosovo refugees and
establishment of transitional administrations. (Germany-NATO-
Yugoslavia) 
</P>
