<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Not to Attend Peace Meeting if Invited as Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
Tuesday told visiting Uzbek Foreign Minister Abdulaziz Kamilov
that they would not attend the proposed meeting of the "Six Plus
Two" if invited as a group.
</P>
<P>
Afghan sources here told Xinhua that Kamilov, who arrived here
Monday on a two-day visit, went to the southern Afghan city of
Kandahar Tuesday morning and held a meeting with Taliban supreme
leader Mulla Omar.
</P>
<P>
Kamilov was told that the Taliban would send a delegation to
the proposed meeting of "Six Plus Two" in Tashkent only if they
are invited as a "government", the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Uzbek foreign minister flew into the Taliban stronghold of
Kandahar Tuesday morning and held wide-ranging talks with Omar and
other senior Taliban leaders, focusing on the Afghan turmoil.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of the "Six Plus Two" group at deputy foreign
minister-level is proposed in Tashkent with expected participation
of Afghan factions. However, the date for the meeting has yet to
be announced.
</P>
<P>
The "Six Plus Two" group comprises Afghanistan's six immediate
neighbors plus Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Kamilov's talks with the Taliban leaders
were highly "constructive" and the two sides agreed to continue
the talks in future.
</P>
<P>
Kamilov is the second foreign minister from a Central Asian
Republic to have visited the Taliban's stronghold in three months.
Foreign Minister of Turkmenistan Sheikh Boris Mradov twice visited
Kandahar before and after the peace talks between the Taliban and
the rival Northern Alliance in Ashgabat in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Omar told Kamilov that his government desires friendly ties
with all countries, especially the neighboring states, according
to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Omar assured Kamilov that the Taliban do not want to export
their ideas to other countries.
</P>
<P>
Kamilov held two-hour talks Monday after his arrival here with
Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz. The two ministers agreed
that the immediate restoration of durable peace in Afghanistan
would bring enormous economic and commercial benefits to the
entire region.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed their full support to the promotion of Afghan
peace process through the United Nations, the Organization of
Islamic Conference and any other means.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and Uzbekistan also agreed that establishment of a
multi-ethnic government in Afghanistan through indigenous Afghan
talks could only guarantee peace and stability in the war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
Both Pakistan and Uzbekistan reiterated that they would
continue their efforts for the promotion of contact between the
various Afghan parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
