<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Botha Wins Appeal Over Truth Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Former South African President
P. W. Botha Tuesday won his Cape High Court appeal on technical
grounds against his conviction for snubbing the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC).
</P>
<P>
The court set aside both the conviction as well as the sentence
of 10, 000 rand (1,600 U.S. dollars) or 12 months imprisonment,
plus 12 months conditionally suspended, imposed by the regional
court in George, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Judge Selwyn Selikowitz, with Judge John Foxcroft concurring,
upheld the appeal on technical grounds, saying the subpoena
calling Botha to testify before the TRC on December 19, 1997 was
invalid.
</P>
<P>
This meant that Botha, who has branded the TRC a "circus," had
not acted unlawfully by failing to appear before the commission.
</P>
<P>
The subpoena, issued on December 5, was invalid because it
called Botha to appear after the TRC's active life span had
expired on December 14.
</P>
<P>
An amendment act prolonging the truth commission's activity was
only promulgated days after the subpoena was issued and was not
retroactive.
</P>
<P>
The TRC therefore did not have the power to call a hearing on
December 19.
</P>
<P>
State prosecutor Bruce Morrison had urged the court to at least
uphold a conviction on the alternative count -- hindering the
commission in the course of its duties.
</P>
<P>
But the judge said the basis for a conviction on the
alternative count was, like the main charge, dependent on the
validity of the notification itself, and the court was obliged to
reject this as well.
</P>
<P>
The judge said he was aware that "there may be many who may
consider that it is unjust" that Botha should escape on technical
point of law.
</P>
<P>
He added: "The TRC was established to perform a noble and
invaluable task. It remains however a statutory body."
</P>
<P>
Botha, 82, did not appear in the Cape Town court for the
appeal, preferring to stay in his luxury seaside home in George, a
coastal city in southern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
His lawyers had argued that the TRC had disregarded its own
legal provisions by issuing the subpoena and had only itself to
blame for the dilemma.
</P>
<P>
The TRC wanted Botha, who ruled with an iron fist between 1978
and 1989, to explain his role in the State Security Council (SSC),
a panel of security chiefs who allegedly condoned the killing of
political opponents and ordered cross-border raids on liberation
activists.
</P>
<P>
The TRC was not able to conclude its work on the SSC before
handing its final report to President Nelson Mandela in October
1998 because of Botha's refusal to cooperate, state lawyers
claimed.
</P>
<P>
The state has the right to appeal against Selikowitz's
decision.
</P>
<P>
Like all senior politicians of the former National Party, which
enforced apartheid and ruled until 1994, Botha claimed to have
known nothing about security force atrocities.
</P>
<P>
But in its final report, the TRC said Botha should be held
accountable for gross human rights violations that occurred during
his 11-year rule, including the killing of political opponents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Receives Letter From Belgrade on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 1 (Xinhua)--German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer
on Tuesday afternoon received a letter from his counterpart in
Belgrade, Zivadin Jovanovic, Bonn's Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Martin Erdmann did not give any
detail of the letter, saying it needs to be studied in following
days.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this day, Yugoslav media has said Belgrade expressed in
this letter its readiness to accept the G-8 principles on solving
the Kosovo crisis. The letter was sent on Monday, it said.
</P>
<P>
G-8, seven leading western industrial nations and Russia, in
May passed a statement of "general principles" on solution to the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The statement demanded a full withdrawal of Yugoslav troops
from Kosovo and deployment of an international peacekeeping force
with NATO at its core.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade's letter was addressed to the chairman of European
Union (EU)'s Council of Ministers, a post that Fischer currently
holds, said Erdmann, adding that the letter has come later
possibly due to some "technical reasons".
</P>
<P>
In a relative development, Fischer on Tuesday warned against a
possible escalation of Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The following days will be decisive," said Fischer in Berlin
at a meeting of EU's committee of national parliaments and the
European Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Patience is needed in current situation, and if the diplomatic
mediations fail, the war will escalate, he said.
</P>
<P>
Later this day, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder is due to
hold a meeting on Kosovo crisis with the EU mediator, Finnish
President Martti Ahtisaari, Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, and
U.S. deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
