<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Chinese Names for Tropical Cyclones to Be Used From 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- New Chinese names for tropical
cyclones will be used with effect from January 1, 2000, the Hong
Kong Observatory announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland, Hong Kong and Macao will adopt the same
set of Chinese names for tropical cyclones to avoid confusion
arising from multiple Chinese translations for any given name, a
spokesman for the Hong Kong Observatory said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the Hong Kong Observatory, the China National
Meteorological Center, and the Macao Meteorological and
Geophysical Services have discussed the subject and agreed to a
common set of Chinese names.
</P>
<P>
The English version of a new list of Asia-Pacific names for
tropical cyclones was adopted by the Typhoon Committee at its 31st
Session held in Manila, the Philippines, at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
From the year 2000, tropical cyclones in the western North
Pacific and the South China Sea will be assigned names from the
list. It consists of a total of 140 names contributed by 14
countries and regions, including 10 names provided by the Hong
Kong Observatory.
</P>
<P>
With effect from the year 2000, the spokesman said, the Tokyo
Typhoon Center of Japan will assign a serial number and a name
from the new list to every tropical cyclone attaining tropical
storm strength.
</P>
<P>
Apart from being used in forecasts and warnings issued to the
international aviation and shipping communities, the name will
also be used officially in information on tropical cyclones issued
to the international press.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Typhoon Committee members will also adopt
these names in their respective regions subject to local
circumstances. The Chinese mainland, Hong Kong and Macao therefore
agreed upon a uniformed set of Chinese names. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
