<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive Meets Former US President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) exchanged views
with visiting former U.S. president George Bush on a number of
issues during their meeting at the Government House here Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Tung updated Bush on the political and economic developments in
Hong Kong since the handover -- the successful implementation of
the "one country, two systems" concept, and how Hong Kong tackled
the financial turmoil and its efforts to create a more prosperous
future for the SAR.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-U.S. relations, Tung said that he believed that not
just Hong Kong and the Asian Pacific region, but the whole world
would stand to benefit from a harmonious relationship between the
two nations.
</P>
<P>
On NATO's attack on the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia, Tung
said that the strong reaction from the Chinese people was only
natural.
</P>
<P>
He called on the U.S. government to complete its investigation
report as soon as possible and give an account to the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
This would be conducive towards improving Sino-U.S. relations,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Cox report, Tung refuted allegations in the
report that there were loopholes in Hong Kong's control system
over strategic commodity trade.
</P>
<P>
Bush is a long-time friend of Tung, and is in Hong Kong on a
private visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
