<HEADLINE> Railway in Northwestern China Cuts International Transport Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Northern Xinjiang Railway
Company announced today that it will rescind or lower some
international railway transport fees.
</P>
<P>
Subsidies for trains used for international freight transport
and charges for trains using the special line linking with the
Alataw Pass Station will be rescinded, and three other types of
fees mainly for international railway transport through the pass,
which is in the northern part of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, will be reduced.
</P>
<P>
The railway section in northern Xinjiang is an important part
of the new Eurasian Continental Bridge. It starts from Urumqi's
West Station and connects with a railway in Kazakahstan at Alataw
Pass. It handles more than six million tons of goods and 1.63
million passengers a year.
</P>
<P>
By cutting fees, the Northern Xinjiang Railway Company will
lose more than 20 million yuan (about 2.5 million U.S. dollars) in
income a year, but it will increase its transport volume and get
more from the new Eurasian land bridge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
