<HEADLINE> Southern China's IT Industry Has Bright Future, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's southern city of
Guangzhou is confident about its information technology industry
becoming a new pillar industry, according to Ping Xingguang,
director of the Guangzhou Information Center.
</P>
<P>
He said that the city's has the right conditions for the IT
industry, with 30,000 kilometers of fiber optic cable and a large,
technologically-advanced and secure public information network.
</P>
<P>
The city's cable TV network reaches 1.2 million families and by
the end of March, when up to 150,000 Internet users had been
registered. Guangzhou has good information sources, with over 300
databases and a number of prominent websites as well as 13 radio
and TV stations and 76 newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's huge market demand for information provides energy
for developing the IT industry, Ping said, and a recent survey
showed that about 31 percent of the families here have computers
and 10 percent more plan to get them in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
About 95 percent of its government departments and 60 percent
of its businesses plan to increase their budgets in information
products and services in the near future.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the city has finalized its plans for IT
industrial development and expect it to become an information
society by the year 2010.  
</P>
