<HEADLINE> SW China Province Bans Smoking in Capital's Public Places </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan Province in southwest China,
which is a major tobacco producer, instituted a ban on smoking in
public places in its capital Kunming today.
</P>
<P>
At Kunming Railway Station, one man who said he has been
smoking for 30 years was stopped by staff members there when he
took out a cigarette and was told that anyone caught smoking in a
public place will face stiff penalties.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of Yunnan's revenue comes from the tobacco
industry, which has been doing very well since the mid-80s. The
percentage of local people who smoke is higher than in some other
parts of China.
</P>
<P>
In Kunming and other provincial cities that are known for their
scenery, smoking has bothered many visitors from outside the
province. So, the ban on smoking is a way to create a clean,
comfortable and healthy social environment, said Zhang Chenggui, a
city government official.
</P>
<P>
The smoking ban covers waiting rooms at airports, ports,
railway and bus stations, recreation centers, sports centers,
education areas, and large shops. Some government and non-
government organizations and military departments will also be
affected.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that they will still need to strengthen the
publicity campaign and law enforcement to really make the ban take
effect.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
