<HEADLINE> International Organizations Donating Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony was held today at the
International School of Beijing (ISB) in recognition of the 1,179,
340 yuan (142,600 U.S. dollars) given by international
organizations to three primary schools in flood-stricken parts of
China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from UNESCO's Beijing office, the American
Chamber of Commerce (AmCham) in China, the American Community Club,
ISB, and other agencies were present as donors along with two
representatives of the provincial capital of Harbin's Education
Commission to receive the donation.
</P>
<P>
It will be used for three primary schools in the Xianfa, Yilan,
and Xin'an areas of Harbin. A 40,000 yuan scholarship fund will
also be set up.
</P>
<P>
The "Working for the Future" donation project began last
October, when AmCham started raising funds among its member
companies to help Heilongjiang rebuild a number of schools that
were destroyed last summer. UNESCO later joined the activity.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO is currently working closely with the provincial and
municipal education commission to ensure the smooth functioning of
the project which started in May and is due to finish on August 15.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony celebrating the completion of the project will be
held on September 8, 1999, United Nations Literacy Day.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO will continue to get funds through various channels to
promote educational opportunities for Chinese children in rural
and poverty-stricken areas, according to Noboru Noguchi, UNESCO
representative to China, Mongolia and the Democratic Republic of
Korea. 
</P>
