<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Stopping Excessive Levies on Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The board will pay special attention to industrial and
commercial administration, environmental protection, construction,
quality supervision, transport, and water conservation fees as
well.
</P>
<P>
The central government will have new national inspections of
fees local authorities levy on enterprises this year and will not
approve any new fees.
</P>
<P>
An SETC official says that these fees can be attributed to
problems in the distribution of revenues by the central and local
governments. At present, all tax revenues other than income tax go
directly to the central government. So, to increase revenues
without central government controls, local governments levy
administrative fees on enterprises and individuals.
</P>
<P>
This has eroded tax revenue base and has led to serious
defaults in tax payments by enterprises. But, over the past 12
months, the central government has removed almost all local fee
authority from local governments. It is trying to turn local fees
into taxes as soon as possible to establish new treasury and tax
systems that meet the demands of a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yuanzhi, the deputy director of the SETC's Enterprise
Supervision Department, says that in the next few weeks the
government will publish 10 major examples of local authorities
charging illegal fees, in the media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Stopping Excessive Levies on Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- To make sure that Chinese and
foreign enterprises don't end up paying the nearly 100 billion
yuan in excessive fees that local authorities charge every year,
the Chinese government is cracking down on unreasonable fee
schemes this year.
</P>
<P>
In the past 12 months, it has stopped these fees in 26,710
cases where government departments and local authorities were
charging enterprises and individuals by cutting the annual
revenues of these departments by 98.5 billion yuan (12 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government ferreted out more than 18,000 cases of such
charges and penalized 1,273 government officials or staff members
who were involved, confiscating 240 million yuan in illegal fees.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Zheng Silin, the vice-minister of the
State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC), the effects of these
measures should not be overestimated and they will take time to
make their effect felt and some areas are still levying illegal
fees.
</P>
<P>
SETC and five other ministries have formed a joint board to
deal with these burdens and it has decided that, based on their
work in the electric power, railway, and public security sectors
last year, it will focus on eliminating unreasonable agent service
fees this year. Some government departments have shifted their
duties to agents that they sponsored and charged fees through the
agents on services that they were supposed to provide to the
public for free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
