<HEADLINE> Two Romanians to Cycle to North Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Two Romanians from the north-
western city of Cluj-Napoca decided to cycle from July 1 to
October 1 across the whole Scandinavian Peninsula, passing beyond
the Arctic Circle in an attempt to reach the North Cape, Europe's
north extremity.
</P>
<P>
Stefan Roman and Mihai Benea planned to cycle as many as 9,000
km within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
It will be a first time for Romania to take in the most
venturesome expedition by cycling over such a long distance, the
official Rompres news agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They will start from Hamburg, pass through Kiel, Copenhagen,
Malmoe, Goeteborg, Oslo and Bergen, then cross the entire
Norwegian shore till Bodo, where the two cyclists will be taken by
ferry-boat to the Lofoten Islands, 500 km from the North Cape.
</P>
<P>
Their way back will pass through Finland, Russia, Estonia,
Lithuania and Poland, with a travel schedule due to comprise the
largest part of historical, natural and cultural monuments along
the route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
