<HEADLINE> Manila to Modernize Its Maritime Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Monday night his administration is committed to supporting
the modernization of the country's maritime industry and making
the Philippines a major shipbuilding center in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 25th anniversary of the Maritime Industry
Authority (Marina) at the Presidential Palace, Estrada said he
will back up efforts of Marina to propose changes in the
Philippine ship mortgage law to facilitate the acquisition of new
vessels.
</P>
<P>
The president said he would direct government agencies
concerned to immediately sit down with Marina so that amendments
in policies and regulations, where necessary, can be drawn up and
implemented as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We will strengthen our maritime industry to enable it to face
and match the challenges of the future," the president emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Paying tribute to the maritime industry's foreign exchange
contributions to the economy worth 1.5 billion U.S. dollars which
representing the 6th largest dollar remittance for the past five
years, the president said the Filipino seafarers are the
modern-day heroes.
</P>
<P>
With the deregulation of the shipping industry, Estrada said so
many routes are now being opened to Philippine ships. "In the
years to come, we can compete with the shipbuilding capabilities
of our neighbors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, he said, can also be proud that at the
beginning of the 1990s, its overseas shipping had one of the
world's largest fleets together with Greece, Japan, the United
States, Russia and Norway. 
