<HEADLINE> British Government Denies GM Rift with Prince Charles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The British government denied on
Tuesday that it disagreed with Prince Charles over genetically
modified food, after the heir to the throne questioned its safety.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think he (Prince Charles) is embarrassing the
government. I think he's raising issues which deserve to be
raised," Environment Minister Michael Meacher said in an interview
with BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
"There are 10 questions in his article, all of them entirely
fair questions. The government is trying to give answers to them.
We're not trying to duck it. We're not trying to evade. We want
the evidence to be put on the table," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an article for Tuesday's Daily Mail, Prince Charles
questioned claims that contend genetically-modified foods are safe.
</P>
<P>
"Do we really need GM food in this country?" asked Charles. "
On the basis of what we have seen so far, we don't appear to need
it at all."
</P>
<P>
Meacher also defended the government's position on genetically-
modified foods, saying the government would not force GM foods "
down people's throats" and would not put public health at risk.
</P>
<P>
However, the environmental group Friends of the Earth, which
has led public opposition of GM foods, said Charles's comments in
the Daily Mail were a blow to the government.
</P>
<P>
"We're delighted by the prince's article," said the group's
director, Charles Secrett. "It's about time the government took
account of the overwhelming tide of opinion on GM foods."
</P>
<P>
Opponents of GM foods and crops claim their long-term safety
and environmental impact have not been assessed, leading to calls
for a moratorium on crop growing until more is known.
</P>
<P>
But the government is keen to exploit the multi-million pound
market, saying GM foods could lead to cheaper and better tasting
foods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
