<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast, Caspian Cooperation Vital for Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) Tuesday urged the Middle East and the Caspian
Sea region to cooperate in the energy field to bring about a
stable oil market.
</P>
<P>
"The two regions can complement each other and cooperate in
the energy field in order to achieve stability in the oil market
and improve revenues for the oil producing countries," UAE
Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources Obeid Bin Saif Al
Nasir said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks at the opening session of the 6th
International Caspian Oil and Gas Exhibition and Conference, which
opened Tuesday at Baku, Azerbaijan, UAE official WAM news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Oil production from non-OPEC (Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries) regions would stabilize and then decline in
the coming decades, and consequently, most of the oil supply to
meet future demand growth should come from the Middle East and
other newly developed areas such as the Caspian Sea region, Nasir
said.
</P>
<P>
In this context, the two regions could play a key role in
meeting the future world demand for energy, and therefore,
cooperation between the two regions in the field was vital for the
stability of the oil market, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister predicted that the current oil supply glut may
not last long and demand for oil will go up in the future.
</P>
<P>
"The world will successfully overcome current and future
economic crises and the oil market situation will continue
improving, enhanced by cooperation among producing countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the world's need for commercial energy is
expected to grow by about 21 percent in the next 10 years and by
nearly 41 percent in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the demand for oil could rise by 17 percent in the
10 years to come and by 32 percent in the next 20 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to natural gas, forecasts indicated even faster
growth rates, reaching nearly 35 percent and 65 percent by 2010
and 2020 respectively, he added.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has the world's third largest oil reserves, which stand
at 98 billion barrels, and the fourth largest natural gas proven
reserves of 6 trillion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is expected to undertake major developments in oil and
natural gas sectors in the future in view of the disparity
existing between reserves and production levels, the minister
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
