<HEADLINE> Factiles of AVC Cup Men's Club Tournament Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, Anhui, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are the factiles of
the teams in the first AVC Cup Men's Club Tournament:
</P>
<P>
1: Sichuan Fu Lan Club of China:
</P>
<P>
A dominating force in the Chinese Volleyball League since the
1990s, it finished the runners-up in 1990 and claimed the league
title the next year. After slumping to fifth in 1992, it re-
surged to grab the silver in 1993 and stepped further to runners-
up and champions in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Its feat was highlighted by three straight league titles. It
first powered to the title in the 1996-97 season when the league
initiated the home-and-away format, and later achieved the double
by winning the Eighth National Games. In the last two seasons, it
held off the tough challenges to retain the league titles twice.
</P>
<P>
2: Chendu Army club of China
</P>
<P>
By finishing second in the 1991 National Championship, the club
was ushered in Serie A.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1995, it kept its fourth place in the National
Volleyball Serie A league but was relegated as it encountered its
worst moments after finishing eighth in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, it backed to Series A after finishing second in the
1997-98 National Volleyball Tryouts and ended up third this season
in the national league.
</P>
<P>
3: Paykan club of Iran
</P>
<P>
The club has won the Iranian League four times with impressive
performances in the major world events.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Iranian club won the International Tournament in
Bangladesh and finished runners-up in another international meet
in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
It was placed third in the ninth Asian Men's Club Championships
in Lebanon in 1997 and climbed to second in the next version.
</P>
<P>
4: Samsung Fire &AMP; Marine Insurance Club of South Korea
</P>
<P>
It was crowned in the second Korean Volleyball Great Festival.
Despite a reshuffle, it has set a record of winning three
consecutive titles from 1997-1999 in Korean Volleyball Super
League, the most recognised volleyball championships in Korea.
</P>
<P>
Also in May 1997, it claimed the title of the ninth Asian Men's
Club Championships in Beirut, Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
5: NEC Blue Rockets of Japan
</P>
<P>
The club won the 42nd All Japan Championships in 1993 and
retained the title next year.
</P>
<P>
After finishing third in 1995, it returned to stand atop the
next year and repeated its feat in 1997 before slumping to third
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the Japanese Volleyball League, another major national event,
it won the V-League twice in 1995 and 1998, twice for third in
1994 and 1996 with one runners-up in 1997.
</P>
<P>
6: Al-Rayan Club of Qatar
</P>
<P>
The team has dominated the Qatar Championship for a long period
and qualified for the AVC Men's Club Tournament as national
champions this year.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this feat, it has won the Seniors Cup in the seasons
of 1984-85, 1988-89, and 1993-94, and dominated the Qatari General
Tournament for Seniors in the seasons of 1992-93, 1994-95 and 1997-
98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
