<HEADLINE> Romania Launches Project to Develop Rural Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government is
planning a nation-wide program to improve schooling and
educational facilities in backward rural areas, the local daily
Nine O'clock reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The program, jointly financed by local authorities, government
allocations, and the World Bank, is aimed at providing more modern
educational opportunities to children living in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
There are already a number of projects under way that benefit
from co-financing on the part of the Romanian government and the
World Bank, including a mini-pilot project for the promotion or
rural information and training centers in five rural settlements
in different counties.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the education in rural schools has continued
to decline because of insufficient funding and the exodus of
teachers' to larger towns. The pupils from the rural area
represent almost half of Romania's school population, but as many
as 40 percent of them do not receive equal opportunity in
education compared to children living in towns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
