<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Success Story of Thai Tourist Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A 7.5 percent increase in terms of
foreign tourist arrivals in Thailand at a time when the country's
gross domestic product slumped by 8 percent marked the success of
Thailand's tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
Pitak Intrawityanunt, minister of the Prime Minister's Office
and top administrator of the tourist industry in Thailand, talked
about the secret recipe of the largest single industry in the
country in an interview with Xinhua on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The success of the industry lies in the marketing mix:
products, prices, promotions and places, which are necessary to
compete in the world market, Pitak said.
</P>
<P>
"We have historic sights in the North, and scenic beaches in
the South. We have modern metropolis like Bangkok, and we also
have well-protected forests in some remote areas," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
"With these diversified destinations, we can serve tourists
with different needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for prices, the currency devaluation which sparked the
financial crisis in mid 1997 made Thailand a much cheaper
destination than it used to be.
</P>
<P>
But, as officials of the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT)
once said that Thai hotels will do nothing that would in any way
reduce the quality of visitors' experience in spite of the
floatation of the baht and pricing pressure.
</P>
<P>
The proof was a survey of "The World's Best Value" holiday
spots published by Travel and Leisure Magazine in March 1999,
which showed that hotels, cities and resorts in Thailand scored
top marks.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok was rated the seventh-best value for money city in the
world, while Phuket, the famous island resort in southern
Thailand, the fourth-best value for money resort.
</P>
<P>
Thai hotels scored particularly well in the survey, with the
Oriental ranking the top value hotel in the world and three other
luxury hotels in Thailand being included in the top five spots in
the category of best value Asian hotels.
</P>
<P>
Promotional campaign is one of the most important parts of the
tourist industry in Thailand. The "Amazing Thailand 1998-1999"
campaign is so successful that the TAT is considering using the
slogan, which, according to Pitak, seems to have been known to
everyone, in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
As part of the "Amazing Thailand" campaign, TAT took advantage
of the rich Thai tradition to introduce various festivals, such as
Water Lantern Festival and Songkran (Water-Splashing) Festival,
whose exoticism foreign visitors find hard to forget.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, another Grand Sale month began in Thailand with the
participation of leading department stores and famous antique and
jewelry shops. The semi-annual campaign is aimed to lure shoppers
from around the world and make Bangkok a regional shopping center.
</P>
<P>
The country is also trying to make Bangkok, the capital, a
world conference center by spending 85 million baht (2.3 million
U.S. dollars) on hosting a number of international conferences.
More

=06011301
NNNN
21:04 21:04 g # HAB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Success Story of Thai Tourist Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition to the marketing mix, Pitak attributed the success
of Thai tourism to the world-class services, stable political
situation and satisfactory public security.
</P>
<P>
"I know that a lot of Japanese girls come to Thailand not only
for sightseeing. They stay here long to learn make-up, cooking
skills," the minister said, "And they feel that Thailand is a safe
and friendly place with nothing to be afraid of."
</P>
<P>
Pitak also said that in a modern society, people are faced with
fierce competition in their working days.
</P>
<P>
"When they are on vacation, they want to be in a relaxing and
pleasant environment, which Thailand can provide with," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand is called 'Land of Smile'," Pitak said, "You can
enjoy world-class services here."
</P>
<P>
Thailand is bragging of the achievement of luring 7.79 million
foreigner tourists to the country and earning 265 billion baht
(6.39 billion dollars) from them in the second year when the whole
region was mired in the economic slump.
</P>
<P>
The TAT expected another big increase of 7 percent in foreign
tourist arrivals in 1999 to 8.2 million with tourism earnings
reaching 300 billion baht (8.1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
To meet that target, Pitak said no market, no matter how small
it is, can be spared to loose.
</P>
<P>
He said he will lead a high-level public and private sector
delegation to visit East Europe to boost tourist arrivals from
this region.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern European market has shown visible growth of 39.4
percent to 48,464 arrivals in 1998 from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
China is another market that TAT attaches greater importance,
which, with world's largest population, has become the fourth
biggest market for Thai tourism with its 600,000 visitors in 1998,
Pitak said.
</P>
<P>
The minister expected to see a rapid growth in Chinese tourists
in Thailand to 800,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Within three years, China will become the largest market for
Thai tourism," he said.
</P>
<P>
As Thailand's largest single industry and the only one to have
seen major growth since the economic recession, tourism is
expected to create around 4 million jobs by the end of this year.
And by the year 2010, the number is predicted to grow to 5.6
million, Pitak said.
</P>
<P>
What's more, tourism revenue is expected to account for 13
percent of the country's total revenue this year.
</P>
<P>
"The government has realized that developing tourist industry
is an effective way to help revive the Thai economy," Pitak said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
