<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Facts &AMP; Figures of South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The second all-race general
election in South Africa is to be held Wednesday. Following is
general information about the country:
</P>
<P>
Official name: Republic of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Location: South Africa occupies the southernmost part of the
African continent, with Namibia, Botswana, Zimbabwe, Swaziland and
Mozambique in the north, and the kingdom of Lesotho completely
enclosed in its territory.
</P>
<P>
Area: 1,219,090 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Population: 40,583,573 (1996). According to the census in 1996,
76.7 percent of the total population were blacks, 10.9 percent
were whites, 8.9 percent were coloreds; 2.6 percent were
Indian/Asian and 0.9 percent belonged to unspecified races.
</P>
<P>
Religion: Almost 80 percent of the population are Christians.
Other major religious groups are the Hindus, Moslems and Jews.
There are also traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
Languages: South Africa has 11 official languages with English
and Afrikaans in dominant position .
</P>
<P>
Capitals: Pretoria (Administrative), Cape Town (Legislative),
Bloemfontein (Judicial).
</P>
<P>
Provinces: South Africa has nine provinces: Western Cape,
Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Free State, KwaZulu-Natal, Gauteng,
North-West, Mpumalanga, Northern Province.
</P>
<P>
Currency: rand (1 rand = 100 cents)
</P>
<P>
Time Zone: Greenwich Mean Time plus two hours.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Parents Shop for Educational Toys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Parents throughout China visited
stores today to find toys to give their children to mark today's
celebrations of International Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
However, a recent survey revealed that some 60 percent of
Chinese parents are far less than satisfied with available toys
and expect stores to introduce new items.
</P>
<P>
The Science Times recently carried the results of a survey
showing that only six percent of parents were satisfied with the
current toy market.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 percent of respondents voiced their preference for
imported toys, especially items featuring cartoon figures. Experts
conducting the survey noted that people prefer the attractive
appearance and high-tech aspects of foreign toys and in turn tend
to avoid purchases of traditional Chinese toys.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 67 percent of responding parents prefer to
buy educational toys, with 60 percent citing a preference to toy
bricks. Over 70 percent expressed they dislike for toys which are
simply fun, but lack any educational value.
</P>
<P>
Experts say this particular factor shows the different
education concepts between parents in China and in western
countries. Chinese parents hope to improve the cleverness of their
children even in play situations.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that 71 percent of Chinese parents consider
the educational value of toys prior to making a purchase, with
some 66 percent placing great consideration on price.
</P>
<P>
Domestically manufactured toys such as dolls are popular on
international markets. Some 50 percent of toys sold in the United
States and 80 percent in Australia were manufactured in China.
Nonetheless, the domestic toy market is far from saturated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
