<HEADLINE> 3 Syrian Workers Wounded in Israeli Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Three Syiran workers were wounded
Tuesday in Israeli air raids on Lebanese guerrillas' targets in
south Lebanon, the Voice of the People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted security sources as saying that Israeli
warplanes fired several missiles on Hezbollah guerrilla's
strongholds in Iqlim Toufah, north of the Israeli occupied border
zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A missile hit a parking plot in the area where three Syrian
workders were wounded, the sources said, adding that they have
been sent to hospitals in Sidon, the country's largest coastal
city in the south.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli raids came hours after Hezbollah killed a member
of Israel's allied South Lebanon Army (SLA) and wounded another by
detonating two separate roadside bombs in Jezzine as the militia
is in the process of departing the town.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is fighting to
oust Israeli occupation forces and SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong SLA is financed and trained by Israel to help
patrol the occupied zone. It also controls Jezzine, a pocket
north of the Israeli occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, SLA's commander Gen. Antoine Lahd announced to pull
his troops out of Jezzine, saying the town is very dangerous to
hold.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 SLA militiamen have been killed and about 400
others wounded in Jezzine over the past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
According to Lahd's plan, the pull-out has formally started
since Monday night and will be over by mid-June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
