<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Share prices edged up slightly on
the Singapore Stock Market Tuesday as retail stocks continued to
hold limelight in dealings.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index rose by 5.02 points to
1908.88 points in active trading.
</P>
<P>
In total, some 1,347.83 million units worth some 1,069.57
million Singapore dollars (about 620.29 million U.S. dollars)
changed hands as losers edged out gainers by 213 to 133 while
another 98 counters closed unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Frt Links topped the most actives chart with a volume of 85.16
million shares traded. IPC was the second most heavily traded
stock that had 75.06 million units done. AFP was the next with
45.26 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SPH 100 was the biggest gainer of the day with a surge of 80
cents to close at 24.50 Singapore dollars. It was followed by
Easyknit which climbed up by 60 cents. DBS, OCBC F and UOB F
picked up 40 cents each to end at 14.3, 13.80 and 11.70 Singapore
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, GE life led the descent of the day giving up
40 cents to close at 21.90 Singapore dollars. A total of six
stocks, including Bukit Sem, C &AMP; C, Creative 50, SIA, SIA F and
SIA DBS c woo incurred a loss of 30 cents.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said retail stocks have stolen the limelight in the
absence of institutional interests in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the rally in retail stocks to actions by
speculative traders, ran out of steam in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
They said the speculation has been damped somewhat by a flurry
of queries from the stock exchange companies on the sharp rise in
prices and trading volume. 
</P>
