<HEADLINE> Shell Takes Over Rwanda's State-Owned Oil Company. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI , June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shell Oil Company has taken
over state- owned oil company, Petro-Rwanda, Jean Pierre
Rubulika, managing director of the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Nineteen Petro Stations in different prefectures of Rwanda
will be taken over by Shell", Rubulika said.
</P>
<P>
According to the head of the National Privatization Secretariat
in Rwanda , Vianney Shumbusho, the approval for the sale of the
petro stations was given by the government and will cost 2.1
million U.S. dollars, according to Rwanda News Agency Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The sale of the company's assets stems from the heavy losses
that have always been incurred, the company owes the government
an outstanding debt of about 4 billion dollars as indicated by
the accounts of December 1998," Shumbusho highlighted. "The
company has more liabilities than assets," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile over 160 oil company workers who were sacked early
this year vowed to sue the company and the government for failure
to pay their six months wages.
</P>
<P>
Petro-Rwanda has got 32 petro stations of which only 17 are
functioning.
