<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Likely to Invest 1.78b Dollars to Install Telephones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government and the
private sector are likely to invest around 86.5 billion taka
(about 1.78 billion U.S. dollars) to install 877,500 new
telephones across the country in the next three years, an English
daily newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government has floated international tenders for 0.3
million phones on "build, own and operate" basis in private
sector, The Financial Express quoted Post and Telecommunications
Secretary Nazmul Ahsan Chowdhury as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government has also agreed in principle to install 50,000
wireless loop telephones by the private sector and 0.2 million
more in collaboration with the Bangladesh Telegraph and Telephone
Board and Japanese private sector, and the total private sector's
investment will be around 32 billion taka (about 659.8 million
dollars), according to the secretary.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations with China and Japan are going on to install
18,900 phones in 58 districts and 0.2 million personal handy
system phones in the city respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
The remaining work of installing 50,000 phones is going on in
Dhaka city, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government will invest 54.5 billion taka (about 1.12
billion dollars) for installation of the new phones, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
At present, the existing tele-density in this South Asian
country is only 0.24 per 100 people against 78 in India, 61 in
Pakistan and 90 in Sri Lanka, and it means that Bangladesh has
only one telephone for 418 people, according a report.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh invests in the telecommunications sector only 0.9
dollar per inhabitant when India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka invest
1.94, 4.40 and 13.1 dollars respectively, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The low investment is one of the prime reason for backwardness
of telecommunications in the country, it pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
