<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Usable Foreign Currency Reserve Hits New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's usable foreign currency
reserve rose to 58.73 billion U.S. dollars at the end of May, up 2.
35 billion dollars from April, according to the Bank of Korea (BOK)
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
If the foreign currency deposits at the overseas branches of
South Korean banks are included, the total of usable foreign
currencies will stand at 61.41 billion U.S. dollars, up 2.15
billion dollars from April.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the increase in foreign currency
reserve to another current account surplus and additional inflows
of foreign capital for corporate and financial restructuring in
May.
</P>
<P>
Last month, one billion U.S. dollars in restructuring funds was
transferred from the World Bank together with an inflow of 240
million dollars in loans from the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
.
</P>
<P>
South Korean foreign currency holdings were once down to less
than four billion U.S. dollars in November 1997 when the nation
borrowed 58 billion U.S. dollars from the IMF after it was gripped
by a financial crisis triggered by corporate bankruptcies and bad
loans of financial institutions in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank said that in the second half, the improvement
of foreign currency reserves will slow due to outstanding payments
to overseas creditors including the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
