<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Sea Fishing Ban Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Several dozen fishing boats
remained berthed today in south China's Lotus Mountain Fish Harbor,
with a sign at the entrance to the wharf clearly announcing -- "
Fishing Ban Begins Today".
</P>
<P>
Chen Caizai, a fisherman in his 50s, was fully aware of the ban,
but nonetheless arrived at the wharf early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
"Fishing has provided a livelihood for generations of my family
and fishing bans were unheard of until now. I know the ban is
designed to protect aquatic resources and must be taken seriously,
" said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Chen said he will repair his trawler and nets during the two-
month moratorium.
</P>
<P>
China's first-ever fishing ban in the South China which will
run through July 31 and will cover one million sq.km. are north to
12 degrees of north latitude.
</P>
<P>
The ban will affect about 300,000 people and 21,000 fishing
boats in south China's Guangdong and Hainan provinces, and the
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The South China Sea, the nation's largest territorial sea area,
enjoys tropical weather and is an ideal fishing ground. Aquatic
resource, however, have shown traces of depletion to overfishing.
</P>
<P>
An investigation carried out by research vessel "Big Dipper"
since December 1997 shows that the density of aquatic resources in
the area has dropped to only 14 percent of the level in 1978, with
the effects readily obvious in six successive fishing seasons.
</P>
<P>
Huang Liangmin, director of the South China Sea Marine Research
Institute under Chinese Academy of Sciences, attributed the
problem to human activities, including the dumping of waste and
reclaiming land from the sea.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics suggest that the number of motorized
fishing boats operating in the South China Sea has grown 10.4-fold,
or 67,000 units, over the past 20 years. The annual harvest of
aquatic products reached 3.7 million tons, a level substantially
above the estimated sustainable maximum of 2.5-2.8 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Local officials note that the fishing ban was enacted during
the spawning cycle for cash fish and will reduce the annual
harvest in the South China Sea by 16-17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Provinces in south China have engaged in an active effort to
better protect aquatic resources and are committed to introducing
advanced fishing methods, including the introduction of a global
positioning system to locate fish shoals, and introducing harsh
penalties for fishermen who engage in hazardous activities such as
introducing electric shocks and dynamiting.
</P>
<P>
Huang pointed out that it will take at least 2-3 years to
determine the effectiveness of the ban.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture began to ban fishing in Summer in
the East China and Yellow seas since 1995, and plans to extend the
moratorium period and no-fishing zone on the latter during 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
