<HEADLINE> Toll In Delhi Fire Rises to 32 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the devastating
fire Monday in Delhi's old town had increased to 32 with 16 more
died of burn injuries, police said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Another 38, including 9 children, were still in various
hospitals in the capital, Deputy Commissioner of police of the
Central District B. K. Singh said.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen people were charred to death on the spot and over 50
others severely injured Monday evening in the fire in the
congested walled city of Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee visited the
injured Monday and instructed the authorities to ensure best
medical attention to the fire victims.
</P>
<P>
The fire was believed to have caused by a chemical explosion in
a chemical shop inside an office building of a transport company,
according to the police.
</P>
<P>
Two buildings were reduced to rubbles and two more suffered
about 60 percent damage in the fire.
</P>
<P>
Many of those caught in the fire got burnt beyond recognition
and they did not get even a fraction of a second to escape,
eyewitnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi government late Monday evening ordered an inquiry
into the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
