<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Drug Exports Grow but Problems Remain, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China witnessed growth in the
export of medicines in the first quarter this year but intensive
efforts are still required to solve problems that would otherwise
hamper the future development of drug exports, industry sources
have warned.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China exported 36,107 tons of drugs valued
at 370 million U.S. dollars during the three-month period,
respective 28 percent and three percent increases from one year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
However, behind the increase are problems including lack of
technology-intensive products, pollution caused by pharmaceutical
enterprises and decrease in the export of patented traditional
Chinese medicines.
</P>
<P>
Raw materials and preparations, including antibiotics, vitamins,
hormones and medicinal herbs, accounted for the bulk of drug
exports in the January-March period, while high-tech products such
as biopharmaceutical products only accounted 5.5 percent, or 3.65
million dollars, of the total, according to Monday's edition of
the International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the growth in the production of vitamins and
other medicines for more exports has also exacerbated
environmental pollution in where the factories are situated,
giving a negative impact on the health of local residents.
</P>
<P>
Another major problem is the drop in exports of patented
traditional Chinese medicines in recent years as low prices for
such export products have prompted many enterprises to shift their
production of traditional Chinese medicine to more profitable
Western drugs.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders have called for greater efforts to develop
new and high-tech drugs with greater competitiveness on
international markets. They have also called for strengthened
controls regarding the development and production scale of
products likely to create pollution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
