<HEADLINE> EU Members to Fish Around Sao Tome &AMP; Principe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Over 70 fishing boats from the
European Union countries will be allowed to fish in the
territorial waters of Sao Tome &AMP; Principe, an African island
country in Atlantic Ocean, according to a deal signed by the
African country and EU.
</P>
<P>
The fishery agreement, signed by Maria das Neves, Sao Tome
Economic Minister and EU representatives here, will allow EU boats
to fish in the African country's waters for three years, for which
the EU pay Sao Tome &AMP; Principe two million U.S. dollars, the
Angolan News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also stipulates that EU will help train personnel
for the African country and build ocean-land communications
system.
</P>
<P>
Sao Tome and Principe is rich in fishery resources, but with
poor fishery capability of only 25 million tons in 1998, about
four percent of the country's Gross Domestic Product.  
</P>
