<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Several leading economic indicators have showed
noticeable improvement in Israel's economy in the first four
months, but experts said it remained in a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
According to a report carried by the Haaretz daily Tuesday,
the industrial production rose 1 percent in February and March,
compared with a 1-2 percent decline from October last year
through January this year.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment remained steady at 8.6 percent, or about 190,000
workforces, throughout the first quarter, slightly up from 8.5
percent during the second half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales rose 10 percent in March, following a 7
percent rise in January and 9 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
In the mean time, the consumer price index (CPI) rose by
0.3 percent in April, the lowest growth rate in the past 35
years for the month of April.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the low CPI growth is a good indication
that the economy is heading for a year of stable prices. They
estimate that inflation for this year may be lower than the
government's projection of 4 percent. Inflation stood at 8.6
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) has approved the
1999 state budget, in which expenditure was set at 6.242 billion
U.S. dollars and revenues were at 5.566 billion dollars, with a
deficit of 676 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
UAE Minister of State for Financial and Industrial Affairs
Mohammed Khalfan Kharbash said the government will not resort to
borrowing to reduce the deficit, the Arabic daily Al Hayat
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new budget reveals an increase in social welfare and
service projects and it is expected to be enforced as soon as
getting sanction from the president.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Arab Fund for Economic and Social Development
will provide Syria with a loan of 30 million Kuwaiti dinars (100
million dollars) to finance its communications development
projects.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Minister of State for Planning Affairs Abdel Rahim Al
Soubel and General Manager of the Arab fund Abdul Latif Al Hamad
have signed an agreement to this effect, the Al Hayat reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the projects aim at improving local,
regional and international telephone services, and meeting the
rising demand of the roughly 1.65 million subscribers in Syria.
</P>
<P>
The project covers establishing new exchanges, expanding the
existing ones and building a digital, microwave and optical
network to link rural districts to principal exchanges and extend
cable networks for local subscribers in various governorates.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- As of June 1, Saudi Arabia will collect
departure fees on travelers who depart from Saudi airports as a
measure designed to increase state revenues.
</P>
<P>
Each passenger will have to pay 50 Saudi Riyals (13.3 dollars)
for departure, Kuwait News Agency quoted the Saudi newspaper
Al-Riyadh as reporting on Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, children, diplomats, sailors, transit passengers as
well as pilgrims will be exempted form the fees, the agency
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
