<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian FM Discusses Mideast Peace with Lebanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Sharaa held talks with Lebanese leaders here on Tuesday on the
latest developments in the Middle East peace process and the
situation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard now to judge the future of peace talks with Israel
in the Middle East," al-Sharaa told a news conference following
his meeting with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and Prime
Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
"We can know Israel's real intentions about reviving
negotiations (with Syria and Lebanon) from where they broke off
only after the formation of (Prime Minister-elect Ehud) Barak's
government is completed," said al-Sharaa, who came here by land
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Labor Party leader Barak defeated outgoing Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the May 17 elections and has
pledged to reopen peace talks with Syria and withdraw Israeli
troops from south Lebanon within a year.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, peace talks on Syria and Lebanon
tracks have been in a standstill as Netanyahu refused to return
Golan Heights to Syria and to unconditionally withdraw from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria, a main power broker in Lebanon, has been insisting that
Syrian and Lebanese tracks not be separated and be carried out
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has
been spearheading a war of attrition to oust the Israeli
occupation troops and their allied South Lebanon Army (SLA)
militia out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on SLA's ongoing withdrawal from Jezzine, an enclave
just north of the security zone, al-Sharaa said the pullback would
not bring any affect on Hezbollah in liberating south Lebanon and
also on Syrian-Lebanese joint stance on peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The SLA militia began to withdraw on Tuesday from Jezzine,
which it has held for 14 years, due to rising casualties caused by
Hezbollah's attacks.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong SLA, established in 1985, are trained and
financed by Israeli troops to help them patrol the border zone.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, al-Sharaa also delivered a message from
Syiran President Hafaz Assad to Lahoud, whose details were not
disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
