<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Acts to Reduce Gas-Pump Spills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Environment Minister
Christine Stewart has proposed new regulations that would slow the
flow of gasoline at the pumps to reduce spills and emissions.
</P>
<P>
The proposed regulations would limit the flow of gasoline to a
maximum of 38 liters a minute. There is currently no national
standard in the country. According to industry officials, the
average pump speed is 40 liters per minute, but some pumps can
reach 52 liters per minute.
</P>
<P>
"These regulations ensure less toxic emissions in our air and
less spilling of gasoline into our ground," Stewart said in a
press release Monday.
</P>
<P>
The environmental benefits of the regulations are a modest, but
crucial, first step to cutting toxic emissions, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Faster flow rates increase the chances of spills as the tank
fills up, and also increase emissions of volatile organic
compounds, which are a major contributor to urban smog.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline also contains benzene, which has been linked to cancer.
The government estimates that emissions from gas-station fill-ups
are responsible for about 6 percent of the daily intake of benzene
by adult Canadians.
</P>
<P>
Environment Canada said the proposed regulations will eliminate
two million liters a year in spills by 2001, decreasing the number
of volatile organic compounds released by 1,500 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
The amount of benzene released will drop by an estimated 15
tons a year, and will also save Canadians about one million
Canadian dollars (680,000 U.S. dollars) in fuel costs annually,
the department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
