<HEADLINE> EU, Japan End Embargo on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union and Japan has
formally ended their five-year freeze on sale of arms and
cooperation on new economic ventures with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
In separate statements issued Monday by Japan and the European
Union General Affairs Council, the countries said the embargo was
being lifted in deference to the ascendancy of President Olusegun
Obasanjo last Saturday, according to Tuesday's This Day, a major
Nigerian daily.
</P>
<P>
"The Government of Japan will study extending appropriate
assistance for Nigeria's efforts for reform and development,"
said the Japanese government's statement.
</P>
<P>
The EU's statement said transparency and the close involvement
of civil society are of utmost importance to gain the confidence
of the Nigerian people.
</P>
<P>
"Confidence at home and abroad is crucial for reviving
international cooperation," said the EU statement, which urged
the new government of Nigeria to make all efforts to substantially
improve its debt payment record to facilitate a rescheduling
option within the Paris Club.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on the EU member sates to support the
reform measures of the government by providing technical and
financial assistance. 
