<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, EU Re-start Development Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and the European Commission
have announced a joint communique in Abuja Monday on re-starting
their development cooperation following Nigeria's return to civil
rule.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the European Union's executive branch,
 expressed its intention to focus the cooperation on the fight
against poverty, promotion of democracy and good governance,
anti-corruption measures and the full integration of Nigeria in
the global economy through promotion of trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
The document was released after the EU lifted all sanctions
against Nigeria the same day.
</P>
<P>
About 495 million U.S. dollars allocated to Nigeria under the
Fourth Lome Convention before 1995 can now be renegotiated,
according to the communique.
</P>
<P>
In addition, negotiations can also be opened on the use of the
new allocation which could be made available to Nigeria, said the
communique issued after discussions by the commission with
Nigerian representatives, the Daily Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to adopt a twin-track approach under which a
"quick- start package" of programs will start in 1999 while the
medium-to-long-term cooperation activities will be agreed on after
the results of a comprehensive programing study are reached.
</P>
<P>
The European Union abolished in October 1998 most of the
sanctions it adopted in 1995 because of the human rights
violations by late General Sani Abacha regime of that time.
</P>
<P>
Until now, however, development cooperation has been limited to
actions in support of human rights and democracy as well as the
activities concentrating on poverty alleviation in the framework
of decentralized cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Until 1995, Nigeria was the EU's largest development
cooperation partner with a total of 1.5 billion dollars allocated
to Nigeria under the four successive Lome Conventions since 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
