<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passive Smoking Affects 600 Million Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Health experts warn that harmful
tobacco smoke adversely affects one in every two Chinese citizens,
especially women and children.
</P>
<P>
Passive smoke has emerged as a common health problem in China
and an estimated 600 million people are regularly subjected to
second-hand smoke, according to Professor He Yao, managing
director of the Chinese Association on Smoking and Health.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) defines a passive smoker as
an individual who inhales cigarette smoke for 15 minutes or longer
at least one day each week.
</P>
<P>
The overall nationwide rate for passive smoking has reached 52.
5 percent, with the rate rising to 57 percent for females and as
high as 70 percent for career women between 20-49. Some 71 percent
of homes, 32.5 percent of public venues and 25 percent of work
places lack smoke-free environment.
</P>
<P>
He, a professor with the Geriatric Institute under the People's
Liberation Army General Hospital, stressed that numerous studies
confirm that passive smoking is harmful to human health and
leading cause of cancer.
</P>
<P>
Males account for the majority of China's 320 million smokers.
Cigarettes currently claim the lives of 2,000 Chinese people daily
and the number is expected to climb to 8,000 per day or three
million annually by the middle of the next century if current
smoking patterns persist, according to a joint Chinese and foreign
study of tobacco-related deaths in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Referee Says Asian Volleyball Has Long Way Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, Anhui, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Asia needs to take time to
catch up with and overtake the European volleyball powerhouses, an
international referee said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Najim Al-Yaqoob, the referee with Qatar volleyball
association, said that the gap between Asian and European
volleyball cannot be bridged through one or two years.
</P>
<P>
"In my view it needs at least ten years to beat them," the
referee stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Because of their dominance in height and jump, the Europeans
can play high ball and power game, that is why they can score
points easily," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The height is not everything but is a main factor in deciding
the outcome of volleyball matches," Hassan said.
</P>
<P>
Hassan came here to referee the AVC Club men's tournament, to
run from June 2-7, involving such elite clubs as Sichuan Fu lan of
China, Chendu Army club, Al Rayan of Qatar, NEC Blue Rockets of
Japan, Samsung Fire &AMP; Marine Insurance club of South Korea and
Paykan of Iran.
</P>
<P>
The referee gave a high opinion of China's volleyball, saying
it is "the best in Asia for the way they play and the characters
they display on the courts".
</P>
<P>
Hassan has judged the Thailand 1993 Asian championships and
Doha 1997 Asia championships as well as 1994 junior championships.
</P>
<P>
He thought China or Japan is the biggest contenders for the
club competition and played down the chances for Qatar.
</P>
<P>
"We have two or three strong spikers but our movement on the
court are too slow, and the new setter is yet to get with the
others in the team." 
</P>
</TEXT>
