<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed lower
again Monday with a record current account deficit putting further
strain on the currency.
</P>
<P>
After resisting selling pressure initially, the Australian
dollar ended in Sydney at 64.60 U.S. cents from 64.97 U.S. cents
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) reported Tuesday the
March quarter current account deficit was 5.71 billion U.S.
dollars, seasonally adjusted, from a revised 5.149 billion U.S.
dollars in the December quarter.
</P>
<P>
The figure was the largest quarterly deficit outcome on record,
but was below economists' forecasts which centered on a deficit of
5.87 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar traded between 64.57 and 64.93 U.S. cents
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Also at the close in Sydney, the Australian dollar was at
0.6190 euro from 0.6211 euro, and at 78.24 Japanese yen from 78.85
yen at the close Monday. 
</P>
