<HEADLINE> Australian Teenager Guilty to Fraud Over Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- An academically brilliant
Australian teenager pleaded guilty to three counts of fraud over
Internet, netting him almost 26,000 U.S. dollars in goods by
illegally obtaining credit card numbers, an Australian court was
told Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The youth, who was 16 at the time and cannot be named because
of being underage, pleaded guilty to three counts of fraud and one
of attempted fraud between October 1997 and February in 1998, the
Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor James Godbolt at the Brisbane District Court in
Queensland state, east Australia, said the teenager accessed a
Polish website which provided the same random number selection
process as banks used to devise credit card numbers.
</P>
<P>
Once he got valid numbers, the teenager used them to buy 37,000
Australian dollars (24,000 U.S. dollars) worth of computer goods.
</P>
<P>
He also attempted to obtain 8,000 Australian dollars (5,200
U.S. dollars) in goods from Dick Smith Electronics.
</P>
<P>
Chief Judge Pat Shanahan said he had only kept the teenager out
of jail because of his youth. He sentenced him to two years'
probation and 100 hours community service.
</P>
<P>
The youth, who is now nearly 18, is studying technology at a
university in Brisbane, capital of Queensland state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
