<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Design Databank for Ancient Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are designing a
databank of ancient lakes to provide important information to
facilitate studies of the ancient climate and help predict climate
changes in the future.
</P>
<P>
The scientists will select some 120-odd Chinese lakes subject
to different climatic conditions and will compile files containing
water level change in each body of water, according to Yu Ge, a
researcher with the Nanjing Institute of Geography and Limnology
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Yu said that some 25 percent of the ancient lakes to be
catalogued have disappeared and most existing lakes have changed
dramatically in terms of area, volume and location. The oldest
lake has a history of over 10,000 years, according to Yu.
</P>
<P>
She said that changes in water levels are closely linked to
precipitation levels, temperatures and other climatic conditions.
The project will be highly valuable for further studies of climate
changes.
</P>
<P>
Yu said that a number of countries, including the United States,
Britain, Germany and France, have established similar databanks
and the establishment of a worldwide database is within sight.
However, she noted that the world database lacks information about
ancient lakes in China and central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Yu, a leading researcher in the field, said the databank will
be translated into English by the end of this year. She also noted
that databank will be published on the Internet as a part of the
worldwide database.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
