<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania in Trade Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's trade deficit
stood at 110.4 million U.S. dollars in April, further
deteriorating from a level of 91.8 million dollars in the previous
month, the central bank said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration was contributed by a significant decrease in
export earnings that went down by 31 percent, coupled with an
increase of 5.3 percent in import bill, the Bank of Tanzania (BoT)
said in the May issue of the monthly economic review.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in export earnings was mainly attributed to the
fall in export volume as well as decline in unit export prices, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from both traditional and non-traditional sectors
decreased by 37.8 percent and 21.4 percent, respectively, over the
review period.
</P>
<P>
Decreases in export volumes of coffee, cotton, sisal, tobacco
and cashew nuts and decreases in export unit prices of cotton and
tobacco caused the decline in traditional export earnings.
</P>
<P>
During the year ending April, trade account recorded a deficit
of 956.7 million U.S. dollars, representing a 41.6 percent
worsening compared with a deficit of 676.9 million recorded in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The trade account deficit deteriorated in the review period
mainly due to a significant increase in imports coupled with a
decline in export earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
