Local trader said there were minimal commercial interest for
dollar Monday but negative sentiment on the shilling encouraged
market players to build on their dollar positions, the East
African Standard reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Four leading banks posted the shilling 70.90/71.20 against the
dollar Monday from 70.40 /71.35 at Friday's close. Two other
commercial banks had the shilling 70.95/71.35 against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Abdalla Abdulkhailik, a treasurer at Citibank, said, "we have
established a trend and no body wants to be caught short. We are
now looking at the level 73-75 level in the next few weeks."
</P>
<P>
Dollar supply from the vial agriculture and tourism sectors
remained severely depressed, said Chris Rwengo from the Standard
Chartered Bank, who added that the bank's reserves had been
dwindling while prospects for a re-establishment of funding from
the International Monetary Fund appeared dim.
</P>
<P>
Currency analysts here said they saw the shilling in the 69 to
71 range against the dollar, with any breach of 72 expected to
trigger Central Bank intervention in the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Import of Cloven-Footed Animals From Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China suspended the import of pigs, cattle and sheep as well as
their products from Guinea as of May 12, according to a notice
released recently by the State Administration for the Inspection
of Import and Export Commodities.
</P>
<P>
The notice said all cloven-footed livestock and side-line
products brought in by travelers or via mail from that country
will be confiscated and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Cloven-footed animals and their products carried by ships,
aircraft or trains that come from Guinea and travel through or
stay for a period in China will be quarantined for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
Seized animals and products smuggled in from that country will
be destroyed under the supervision of nearby quarantine
departments, the notice said.
</P>
<P>
Sheep, goats and cattle which have contracted the disease often
show symptoms in their mouths and hooves, hence the name of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Blisters and ulcers appear inside their mouths and in and
between their hooves, and their horns split after the disease is
contracted.
</P>
<P>
Foot-and-mouth disease affects human beings only if they have a
wound or abrasion and are in direct and steady contacts with
infected animals, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The disease can affect milk and meat products from the infected
animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Industrial Production Value Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam achieved an industrial
production value of 67,939 billion Vietnamese dong (4.887 billion
U.S. dollars) in the first five months of this year, a
10.2-percent year-on-year increase, Vietnam News Agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-invested enterprises increased their industrial value
by 22.5 percent, continuing to spearhead the industrial production
growth.
</P>
<P>
The state-run sector increased its value by 3.7 percent and the
non-state sector by 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Big increases were recorded in the output of crude oil, up by
30.6 percent; fertilizers, up by 13.6 percent; bicycle, 22.4
percent; motorcar assembling, almost 53 percent; fishery
processing, over 18 percent; and motorbike assembly, 45.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Because of poor marketing some industries recorded sales and
production decreases. For example, coal production was down almost
19 percent, rolled steel down 19.6 percent and TV set assembling
down 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Vietnam's industrial production in the first five
months was below expectations, Vietnamese Cabinet members said at
a monthly meeting here last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
To address the setback, they decided to take effective measures
in June such as to tackle market and purchasing power difficulties
to promote industry and to stimulate economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
