<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy Departs for Bonn Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian special envoy on Yugoslavia
crisis Viktor Chernomyrdin left for Bonn Tuesday for another round
of talks with Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari and U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
"We are flying to Bonn with new proposals developed by the
Russian side and approved by the president," Chernomyrdin said
before departure.
</P>
<P>
He said the coming stage of negotiations should become
decisive. "We hope to arrive at positive results," the Interfax
news agency quoted Chernomyrdin as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This week should bring us to a definite decision to switch
the military conflict to a political channel," he said.
</P>
<P>
The readiness of the West to compromise "will be seen in Bonn,
" Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
"The West should realize all the negative aspects of what may
happen if a political solution is not found.
</P>
<P>
"The foundation for a political settlement has been formed and
the most difficult thing - its implementation mechanism - should
be coordinated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
has accepted the  settlement principles defined by Russia and the
seven richest Western countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite possible to bring to the negotiating table
representatives of the Serbian side and Kosovo Albanians,"
Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
From Bonn Chernomyrdin will fly to Belgrade Wednesday to meet
with Milosevic. If the talks in Bonn turn out to be successful,
his trip to Belgrade, the fourth since NATO started air strikes 69
days ago, will be accompanied by Ahtisaari. 
</P>
</TEXT>
