<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade of Ho Chi Minh City Appears Signs of Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City's trading activity
in May showed a little growth compared to April but signs of
slowdown have appeared, Vietnam's English business newspaper The
Saigon Times Daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The total sale of goods of the Vietnam's biggest economic hub
stood at 11,318 billion Vietnamese Dong (about 800 million U.S.
dollars), a rise of 1.02 percent over April, the lowest
month-on-month increase since the beginning of the year, The
Saigon Times Daily quoted a report from the city's Service of
Trade as saying. The figures were 1.65 percent, 5.02 percent, 1.51
percent and 1.68 percent respectively in the previous four months,
it added.
</P>
<P>
In May, Ho Chi Minh City exported 399 million dollars worth of
products to gain a trade surplus of 90 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the month the city spent 309 million dollars on imports, a
1.8 percent rise over April, raising the total import value in
five months of this year to 1.4 billion dollars, a 4.3 percent
drop from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that trading at major markets and commercial
centers continued to be thin, and purchasing power has kept on
falling after the Lunar New Year in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index of the city in May declined by 0.2
percent from April. But compared to January it raised by 2
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 09:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Morteza Alviri Elected Tehran Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The city council of Tehran on
Tuesday appointed Morteza Alviri, a well-known moderate
technocrat, the mayor of the Iranian capital of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Republic News Agency reported Alviri was
unanimously elected Tehran mayor by the council members with
secret ballots.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in Iran's history that the mayor for the
capital was elected by a city council.
</P>
<P>
The sitting current council was fromed on the basis of an
election in February, also the first time since the Islamic
revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The post of Tehran mayor has been vacant since former mayor
Gholamhussein Karbaschi was put on trial last June on graft
charges. Karbaschi was imprisoned in April to serve a two-year
jail term.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Tehran city council had been in a month-long
white-hot debate over the election of the city mayor due to
serious differences among political factions, even though the
council was dominated by moderates.
</P>
<P>
Alviri, born in 1948, currently serves as advisor to Iranian
moderate President Mohammad Khatami and Secretary General of the
Organization of Iran's Free Trade Zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-DPRK Ties Important: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The maintaining of friendly
relations between China and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) are conducive to peace and stability in the Asia-
Pacific region, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao here
today.
</P>
<P>
China will contribute its efforts to consolidating and
developing the Sino-DPRK relations, Zhu said in a regular press
conference this afternoon, when asked to comment on the imminent
visit by President of the Presidium of DPRK Supreme People's Court
Kim Yong Nam.
</P>
<P>
China and DPRK are friendly neighbors sharing traditional
friendship and cooperation. Currently, the two countries have been
conducting normal exchanges in political, economic, cultural and
all other fields, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu believes that Kim Yong Nam's upcoming visit will further
push forward the traditional friendship and cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Kim is expected to discuss with Chinese
leaders on regional and international issues of common concern,
but so far, the two sides have had no agreements to sign during
the visit, Zhu added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
