<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Farmers Lambast U.S. Tariff Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- About 200 New Zealand farmers
Tuesday gathered in front of the United States Embassy in
Wellington with a dozen lambs in protest against the expected
tariffs on New Zealand lambs.
</P>
<P>
They urged the U.S. President Bill Clinton to reject the
proposal by the U.S. International Trade Commission (ITC) to
impose tariffs and quota restrictions on lamb imports from New
Zealand and Australia.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton will decide by Saturday whether to sign a
bill imposing trade restrictions on New Zealand and Australian
meat imports.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators held placards and streamers with slogans such as
"NZ, Bleed by U.S. Lamb Tariff," "Subsidies Slaughter Sheep
farmers," and "Mr. Clinton, We need those exports. Don't send our
people of South land into despair."
</P>
<P>
They said they want to send a strong message to President
Clinton before he makes the decision.
</P>
<P>
Most of the demonstrators came from South land, one of New
Zealand's most important sheep meat producers, which is about a
thousand kilometers away from the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the gathering outside the U.S. Embassy, three
mayors, who led the protest farmers to Wellington, and
representatives from various political parties and business
organizations expressed their great concern about and lambasted
trade barriers the U.S. Administration is likely to impose
against New Zealand and Australian Lamb imports to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
They also strongly criticized the U.S. for saying something,
but doing the opposite.
</P>
<P>
"I'm ashamed by standing outside the Embassy of the United
States, which calls itself the flag-bearer of free trade, to
protest against its trade barriers," one representative said.
</P>
<P>
Malcolm Bailey, president of the NZ Federated Farmers, the
organizer of the protest, said the protest sent a clear message
that the U.S. ITC's proposals are "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
At the end of the demonstration, the farmers handed in a
protest letter to the Embassy.
</P>
<P>
A similar protest was also held outside the U.S. Consulate
General in Auckland Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
