<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Back grounder: Positions of S. Africa's Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, June 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's main political
parties which will take part in the June 2 election have outlined
their positions on the following issues:
</P>
<P>
Crime
</P>
<P>
-- The African National Congress (ANC): promises to
drastically reduce the number of guns in circulation and introduce
tougher gun controls;
</P>
<P>
-- The New National Party (NNP): promises "no mercy for
criminals" and a zero-tolerance policy of arresting all criminals
even for "low-level" crimes;
</P>
<P>
-- The Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP): pledges to introduce a
program to cut crime by 25 percent in its first year in
government;
</P>
<P>
-- The Freedom Front (FF): would reintroduce the death penalty
for serious crimes including murder, armed robbery and rape;
</P>
<P>
-- The democratic Party (DP): proposes an integrated strategy
to greatly improve the performance of the police, prosecutors and
courts;
</P>
<P>
-- United Democratic Movement (UDM): offer a range of civil
order proposals which it says will guarantee every citizen's basic
constitutional right to safety of person and property.
</P>
<P>
Employment
</P>
<P>
-- African National Congress (ANC): to introduce
labor-intensive investment throughout the economy, as well as the
promotion of sectors that have large employment potential like
tourism, manufacturing, small and large-scale agriculture and
labor-intensive beneficialness of raw materials;
</P>
<P>
-- New National Party (NNP): to achieve sustainable economic
growth in a socially responsible free-enterprise economy, flexible
labor markets where individuals compete for jobs on the basis of
merit, and the scrapping of the Employment Equity Act and the
revision of other labor legislation;
</P>
<P>
-- Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP): to restructure the public
service to increase spending on service delivery;
</P>
<P>
-- Freedom Front (FF): to create an environment conducive to
foreign and domestic fixed investment;
</P>
<P>
-- Democratic Party (AP): proposes to free the economy by
scaling back red tape hampering job creation and entrepreneurship,
speeding up privatization and promoting foreign investment,
</P>
<P>
-- United Democratic Movement (UDM): says its "road map to
guide South Africa to a world-class nation in 10 years" takes the
route of empowering all through enterprise development.
</P>
<P>
Education
</P>
<P>
-- African National Congress (ANC): promises to move as
rapidly as possible to " free, dynamic and compulsory" education;
</P>
<P>
-- New National Party (NNP): supports for educational
institutions, recognition of the central role of teachers and
parents, ending of the mass retrenchment of teachers, and
empowerment of local school governing bodies;
</P>
<P>
-- Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP): promises to reintroduce
discipline into education, putting an end to anarchy in schools.
</P>
<P>
-- Freedom Front (FF): says its plan for education would ensure
that qualification would be recognized internationally;
</P>
<P>
-- Democratic Party (DP): proposes a total overhaul of the
education system to ensure a dramatic improvement in the quality
of teaching;
</P>
<P>
-- United Democratic Movement (UDM): to achieve greater
accountability, improve community involvement in management and
equitable distribution of resources, and ensure that education and
training facilities would be " clustered" in a geographical area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Issue Transitional Stamps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Macao Posts and
Telecommunications Department will issue a set of stamps on June
2, which can be used both in the period before Macao's handover
from Portugal to China on December 20 and after.
</P>
<P>
The ten kinds of stamps, each with 1.5 million pieces, feature
major modern buildings in Macao which were completed in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, relevant first-day envelops, postcards and
introduction sheets will be available.
</P>
<P>
The set of stamps will be the seventh of its kind issued by the
department this year. In the later half of the year, it will issue
several new sets of stamps which can only be put on mails before
the handover.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the department will issue two sets of stamps on
December 19 and 20 to mark the handover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
