<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Railways to Attract Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Railways is likely to attract
serious investors when it is commercialized, Zambia Privatization
Agency has said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail newspaper Tuesday quoted the agency's
technical director and acting chief executive Stuart Cruickshank
as saying that so far, there are about seven serious investors
awaiting a green light from the central government on the mode of
the privatization the railway company would take.
</P>
<P>
"The seven investors are serious and good people who are ready
to revamp the operations of the railway system in the country," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Cruickshank, the railway company has shown signs
of being a blue chip and is expected to reverse the common
problems faced by various firms that did not attract investors,
ending up being privatized at far lower prices than planned for.
</P>
<P>
Railway transport analysts have indicated that Zambia Railways
is expected to be given to private investors on a franchise basis.
</P>
<P>
It is also envisaged that it would be split into three
categories: goods freight, passenger freight and communications.
</P>
<P>
According to the privatization agency, a total of 242 state-run
firms have been privatized so far, out of a working portfolio of
280 companies. A key feature of the privatization program over
the next phase in Zambia will be the new government policy
guidelines on private sector participation in strategic areas of
the economy. The government has approved the concessions of
Zambia Railways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
