<HEADLINE> Sea Bridge Completed in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zhujiajian Bridge, the first
sea bridge on the East China Sea, opened to traffic Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 2,706-meter bridge links Zhoushan Island and Zhujiajian
Island, two major islands in the Zhoushan Archipelago in east
China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the bridge commenced in 1996 and the project
was completed at a cost of nearly 270 million yuan (32.5 million
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bridge is one of six bridges the city of Zhoushan plans to
construct to link the archipelago with Ningbo, a coastal city in
Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The Zhoushan Archipelago, which has well over 1,000 islands,
features a large number of popular tourist attractions and is a
major fishing ground.
</P>
<P>
The six bridges will be completed at an estimated cost of 5.8
billion yuan, with the remaining five bridges scheduled for
completion in the year 2010.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
