<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' merchandise exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippines' merchandise exports for
the first four months of 1999 grew by 12.1 percent to 10.198
billion U.S. dollars from 9.101 billion U.S. dollars last year,
the country's National Statistics Office (NSF) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report of NSF also showed that exports for April went up by
2.7 percent to 2.345 billion U.S. dollars from 2.285 billion U.S.
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
For April alone, electronics exports, which accounted for 56
percent of the aggregate, grew by 8.2 percent to 1.314 billion
U.S. dollars from 1.214 billion U.S. dollars of the same month
last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of ignition wiring sets increased by 26 percent in
April, while the woodcraft and furniture registered a 2.2 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, earnings from exports of
Input/output/peripheral units declined by 7.1 percent to 140.55
million U.S. dollars from 151.28 million U.S. dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Exports of articles of apparel and clothing accessories also
dropped by 13.3 percent to 133.36 million U.S. dollars from 153.87
million U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Led by Electronic Equipment and parts, manufactured goods
accounted for 89.5 percent of the aggregate and posted a 4.6
increase from 2.0 billion U.S. dollars last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the United States remained the first
exporting market of the Philippines by purchasing 30.7 percent of
the country's goods in April.
</P>
<P>
Other major buyers are Japan, Singapore, the Netherlands,
Taiwan, Hong Kong and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
