<HEADLINE> Barak Intends to Jump to Final Status Talks: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak is considering whether to, through consultations with
the United States and the Palestinians, drop the latest interim
peace agreement and jump to final status talks, the Haaretz daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Labor sources as saying Barak's consideration
is based on the premise that the broad coalition he is trying to
put together will have the necessary political clout to make a
final status deal, making the interim steps stipulated in the Wye
agreement unnecessary any more.
</P>
<P>
After carrying out the first of the three stages of troop
redeployments stipulated in the Wye agreement, outgoing Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu froze the implementation of the
agreement less than two months after he signed on it last October.
</P>
<P>
Barak trounced Netanyahu in Israel's general elections on May
17 on a platform which included a pledge to move forward the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and the U.S. have called on Barak to carry out
the remaining stages of the Wye agreement immediately after he
forms a new government. Barak has until early July to put together
a coalition.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are concerned that Barak might have no much
room for maneuvering in pushing the peace process forward since he
is considering to include right-wing parties such as the Likud and
the National Religious Party in his government.
</P>
<P>
The Labor sources said even if Barak decides to bypass the Wye
agreement, he would talk to Washington and the Palestinians first
as the accord is an international agreement signed by the
government of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
