<HEADLINE> Australia to Ban Japanese Fishing Boats Over Tuna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Australia will ban Japanese
fishing boats from Australian ports and fishing zones following
Japan's decision to ignore international quotas on threatened
Southern Bluefin Tuna.
</P>
<P>
Japan has announced it will again conduct an "experimental
fishing program" for the tuna - the same method it used last year
to take 1,400 tons or 25 percent above its quota.
</P>
<P>
Japan's announcement has prompted an angry reaction from
Australia, member of the Commission for the Conservation of
Southern Bluefin Tuna.
</P>
<P>
"We believe this is totally unacceptable and we are protesting
in the strongest possible terms," Australian Agriculture Minister
Mark Vaile told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"(Australian) Foreign Minister Alexander Downer has called in
the Japanese Ambassador this evening to express those strong
concerns.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely disappointing. It is flying in the face of
Japan's international obligations under the International Law of
the Sea."
</P>
<P>
Vaile said Japan's continued overfishing of the highly prized
tuna was threatening an Australian export industry worth 110
million U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Vaile said Australia was considering taking legal action
against Japan and would pursue the issue through international
forums and treaties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
