<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Prices to Hit Kenya's Key Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's major exports and consumer
goods will be affected by a depressed world market, with some
commodities unlikely to recover after more than four years.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive review of global commodity markets prepared by
the World Bank said some commodities that will suffer from the
falling prices, a weak world economy and a glut in the world
market are tea, coffee and sugar, the East African Standard
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tea and coffee are Kenya's leading export items and major
foreign exchange earners.
</P>
<P>
The review said the poor performance of the global economy is
expected to face a second year of slow growth this year.
Developing countries such as Kenya are not expected to register
any meaningful growth until 2001.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya tea sector is one of the areas expected to take a
beating mainly because of higher output and better quality from
other key producers such as Sri Lanka, the review said, adding
that last year, Kenya produced 280, 000 tons of the 2.89 million
tons of tea produced in the world, and exported 264,000 tons,
coming second to Sri Lanka which exported 217,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Although Kenya led in the world in tea export in 1995 and 1996,
 agricultural experts now predict that the country is unlikely to
reclaim its leading role in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The review noted that tea production in Kenya for the first
quarter of this year was lower compared to last year following an
extended period of dry weather .
</P>
<P>
In addition to dry weather, other problems confronted with
Kenya's tea sector are older tea trees and poor leaf collection
caused by poor roads, the review said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is also facing strong tea sectors in Uganda, Malawi and
South Africa, which are fighting for a larger share of Kenya's
market in Britain, Egypt and Pakistan that account for 83 percent
of the country's export market.
</P>
<P>
Other commodities such as sugar are also expected to suffer
from low prices. Sugar production has exceeded consumption for
the fourth consecutive year and stocks are near record levels.
</P>
<P>
The review predicted that coffee production will reach record
levels in 1999 and exceed consumption by between eight and nine
million bags. Coffee prices have drastically fallen mainly to
currency depreciation in Brazil, a major producer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
