<HEADLINE> Qinghai Continues to Reduce Poverty-Stricken Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The total population of poverty-
stricken people in northwest China's Qinghai Province has dropped
dramatically to one fourth of the level in early 1994.
</P>
<P>
A total of 860,000 farmers and herdsmen have escaped poverty
over the past five-odd years, with the current poverty-stricken
population standing at 330,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The goal of a massive poverty relief project initiated in 1994
centers on ensuring all poverty-stricken people have access to
adequate food and clothing by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the province has accelerated the construction of
basic facilities and harnessing rural and grassland areas subject
to drought. Qinghai has also established more township enterprises
and expanded preferential treatment to promote economic
development in key poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The per capita income of the poverty-stricken population
reached 1,128 yuan in 1998, up some 30 percent on the previous
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
