<HEADLINE> Debt-Ridden Jordanian Telecom Seeks Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The heavily indebted Jordanian
Telecommunications Company (JTC) has asked for a loan of 73
million dinars (102.2 million U.S. dollars) from the government to
keep it running and finance future projects.
</P>
<P>
The government loan, if approved, would be used to introduce a
new mobile telephone system, the Internet project and the
installation of 200,000 additional telephone lines, Jordan Times
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The JTC now carried a debt of 95.5 million dinars (139.3
million dollars) and needed investments of some 322 million
dinars (450.8 million dollars) in the coming four years, Minister
of Post and Telecommunications Jamal al-Sarayreh was quoted by the
paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The JTC could hardly pay its employees` salaries in the coming
years until new investments are made either by attracting a
strategic partner or by offering shares to the public, al-Sarayreh
said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sarayreh added that the JTC would continue to be the only
provider for regular telephone service until the year 2003 when a
license for another company would be issued.
</P>
<P>
The JTC hoped to provide mobile phone and Internet services
through a company under it before the end of 1999, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Mobile Telephone Services (Fastlink) had been the only
one cell phone network in the desert kingdom, but its monopoly in
the industry expired last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
