<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Upsurge Relented in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The upsurge of highland malaria in
Kisii and Gucha districts in Nyanza Province, southwestern Kenya,
has relented, the provincial medical officer Ambrose Misore has
said.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of the disease in the province over the past four
weeks killed some 150 people and more than 2,500 people were
admitted to local hospitals and clinics.
</P>
<P>
Misore said some 200 people were still admitted at the district
hospital and the majority of the dead were children, the East
African Standard reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The medical officer said in a statement that adequate drugs
have been procured and his staff are ready to deal with further
outbreaks of the scourge.
</P>
<P>
Misore also noted that treatment was being carried out
carefully because the disease had become resistant to chloroquine
and other drugs, adding that the surveillance on the malaria
outbreak was going on.
</P>
<P>
He attributed to the outbreak of the disease to the heavy rains
in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Arrives in E. Timor to Prepare for Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations special
representative for East Timor's popular consultation, Ian Martin,
has arrived in Dili, capital of East Timor, on Tuesday to start
his mission in preparing the direct ballot on the territory's
autonomy package.
</P>
<P>
Martin, who is also the head of the U.N. Assessment Mission on
East Timor (UNAMET), was welcomed by local government officials
and some members of the UNAMET.
</P>
<P>
The mission will comprise up to 280 civilian police, an
international staff of 241, 420 United Nations volunteers, and
some 4,000 local staffers.
</P>
<P>
"I have arrived here to carry out the duty mandated by the U.N.
secretary general to prepare and conduct a free and democratic
popular consultation for East Timorese," Antara News Agency quoted
Martin as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. presence in the region will be neutral and not take
sides with certain groups. It will cooperate with all groups in
East Timor to get more information for the success of the direct
balloting, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Indonesia and Portugal on May 5,
the United Nations will deploy civilian police advisers from
several countries to assist Indonesian police to maintain law and
order. A key function will be the disarmament of rival factions
that are either for or against independence.
</P>
<P>
The August 8 ballot will allow the territory's people to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
In the direct vote, East Timorese aged 17 years or above have
the right to vote whether they accept the wide-ranging autonomy
package. If they reject it, the Indonesian government will
consider a separation of the province from the country's
territory.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations will support the result of the direct
balloting, whether the East Timorese accept or refuse the autonomy
package, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
"With the U.N. civilian police presence in cooperation with the
Indonesian Police, UNAMET will assure that the tripartite
agreement is implemented by the Indonesian government," Martin
added.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has assured the United Nations and
the international community that it can control security and order
in East Timor in the run-up to the scheduled August 8 ballot.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
