<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Bodies Asked Not to Comment on Bangladesh Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina has asked foreign organizations working in the country not
to make any public comment on the country's internal affairs, a
press report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Hasina asked her cabinet members at a regular weekly cabinet
meeting on Monday to communicate to foreign missions in the
country to refrain from making any public comment on the country's
internal affairs, The Daily Star newspaper quoted cabinet sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said a recent comment by World Bank Country Director
Federick Temple about the government's claim of a 5.2 percent
growth rate in 1998-99 prompted the prime minister to issue the
instruction.
</P>
<P>
Temple told a meeting on Sunday with members of the Foreign
Investors' Chamber of Commerce and Industry: "5.2 percent looks
miraculous, if you look at broad economic situation and the last
floods."
</P>
<P>
He said the bank had estimated the growth rate would be around
3-4 percent supplemented by good boro crops - an irrigational
paddy variety. The government had projected a growth rate of
3.8 percent in 1998-99 at the donors' consortium meeting in April
this year.
</P>
<P>
Although the economy saw good development in boro crops, the
donor representative said, the manufacturing sector and exports
did pick the way everybody thought.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was badly hit by a prolonged flood last year, which
lasted from July to September, affecting two-thirds of the country
and causing an estimated loss of 4.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to some ministers, Temple's public comment amounted
to interference in the country's internal affairs, and one of the
ministers observed that Temple sounded like a politician belonging
to the country's opposition camp, the sources was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Hasina asked her colleagues, especially the foreign minister
and the finance minister, to communicate to international
financial institutions and other foreign organizations concerned
that they should not make public comments on the internal affairs
of the country.
</P>
<P>
If they had anything to say on any issue, they were free to
communicate it to the government, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Court on Rwanda Gets 3 New Judges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Three new judges of the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) were sworn in
Monday in Arusha, northern Tanzania, the court said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
The judges were sworn in at the opening ceremony of the sixth
plenary session of the court based in Arusha Town.
</P>
<P>
Mehmet Guney of Turkey and Erik Mose of Norway were appointed
last November to replace the judges who did not seek re-election
to a second term of office.
</P>
<P>
Asoka de Zoysa Gunawardana of Sri Lanka, replaces Judge
Dionysios Kondylis of Greece who resigned from Trial Chamber III
on March 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
Their appointments bring to nine the total number of judges of
the trial chambers of the tribunal, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In a speech after the swearing-in, legal counsel Hans Corell,
representing United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
commended the work being done by the tribunal in bringing to
justice the planners and ring leaders of the 1994 Rwanda genocide.
</P>
<P>
Corell also reaffirmed the secretary-general's support for the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Before his appointment to the tribunal, Guney was an ambassador
in the Turkish diplomatic service and in 1998 led his country's
delegation to the United Nations Diplomatic Conference on the
Establishment of an International Criminal Court.
</P>
<P>
Mose served as Judge of the Borgarting Court of Appeals, Oslo.
Gunawardana was a Judge of the Court of Appeals of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The plenary session will continue until the end of this week
with several meetings at which judges will discuss amendment of
the Rules and Procedure and also elect a new president for a
mandate of two years.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. court on Rwanda was created by the U.N. Security
Council in November 1994 after the genocide took place in the
middle of that year. More than 500,000 people were reportedly
killed in the genocide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
