<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children in Xinjiang Become Healthier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Over 5.2 million children of various
ethnic groups in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region have become stronger and fitter in recent years thanks to
the establishment of a health care network.
</P>
<P>
So far, 97 percent of township-run clinics have set up
maternity and child-care centers. A regional network for women and
children at the county, township and village levels has also taken
shape to offer immunity, disease prevention and treatment services.
</P>
<P>
"The incidence of measles in Xinjiang had dropped by 92 percent
in the 20 years ending 1998 and the mortality rate of this disease
was reduced by 98 percent," said a local medical official.
</P>
<P>
The mortality rate of infants has declined from 69 per thousand
in 1990 to 30 per thousand last year.
</P>
<P>
To curb the increase of mentally retarded children as a result
of iodine-deficiency, the regional government has provided
injections of iodized oil for 3.65 million child-bearing women and
spread the use of iodine-rich salt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Remove Industry Protective Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's protective tariff
measures currently being enjoyed by local industries will
gradually fall away, making companies more efficient and
competitive in line with international trade requirements.
</P>
<P>
Tariff Commission Chairman Dzikamai Danha said Monday that
protective tariff measures would apply to infant industries in
future but would eventually be removed as the industries graduate
to fully-fledged businesses, the daily Herald newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will protect them as infant industries by giving incentives
to those involved in production, but over time, the protection
will fall away," he said.
</P>
<P>
Too much protection would lead to inefficiency and at the end
of the day the commission would fail to achieve its objectives,
Danha said, adding there was nowhere in the world where
industrialists would find zero tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The industrialists "must fully utilise their competitive
advantages and fiercely develop niche markets in the domestic and
regional markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
The commission was established through the Tariff Commission
Act of 1998 to investigate tariff changes, unfair trade practices
and identify anomalies in the tariff book, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was also tasked with the reviewing of the current tariff
book and recommending rates that reduce the need for ad hoc relief
measures.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the economy, the chairman said the government had
failed to fully utilise the abundant expertise within and outside
the ruling party to develop the economy.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment the economy is in a fluid state, nobody knows
what should be done to get the economy tick in the direction of
growth and development," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Danha, the country had good infrastructure, a good
human resources base and many more resources, which could be
pieced together and take up the challenges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Automotive Industry Expects Rapid Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
automotive manufacturing region, will be able to produce 400,000
cars annually by 2001, with its domestic market share increasing
to 40 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xianglin, president of the Shanghai Motor Vehicle Group,
said that the city will raise about one billion yuan annually over
the next few years for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai first made cars by imitating Mercedes Benz products in
the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The auto industry began to enter a new period of technological
progress as the city moved to set up two joint ventures with two
of the world's automotive giants, Germany's Volkswagen and the
United States' General Motors, during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
One of them, Shanghai Volkswagen, developed the Santana 2000
cars through a joint design with Volkswagen's overseas firms in
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Currently, it has an annual production capacity of 250,000
Santana cars, with a 92 percent localization rate and more than 90
percent of the parts are made in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai General Motors Corp., the other Sino-foreign auto
manufacturer with an investment of 1.52 billion U.S. dollars, is
the largest Sino-U.S. joint venture in China.
</P>
<P>
It came into production in April and its daily output is
expected to climb to 250 Buick cars by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
In the years to come, according to Chen, Shanghai will
transform its auto industry into a major part of its economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Gets New Research Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Academy of Social
Sciences has opened its new Research Center on Shanghai (RCS), an
institution which will study the history and present condition of
the largest industrial and commercial city in China.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has formed definitive characteristics over the past
150 years by absorbing cultural achievements from other parts of
the country, as well as from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Research into the history and current conditions of the region
will be of great importance for studying the country as a whole,
according to Director Yu Xintian.
</P>
<P>
She noted that research institutes from the United States,
Germany, France, Britain and a number of other foreign countries
have expressed interest in related studies.
</P>
<P>
The center will focus on major subjects concerning the city.
The initial list of topics includes an Introduction to Shanghai
Studies, Protection and Application of Shanghai's Cultural
Heritage, and Urban Development and Social Changes in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
An advisory committee consisting of senior specialists will be
established to guide the center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
