<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 07:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militiaman Killed Amid Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A member of the pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA) was killed and another wounded overnight during
Lebanese guerrillas' attacks at a time when the militia is
expected to withdraw from Jezzine on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese security sources said the SLA soldier was killed by a
roadside bomb when his armored car was driving from Jezzine toward
the Israeli occupied zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Jezzine, just north of the Israeli occupied zone, has been
controlled by SLA since 1985. But on Monday it announced to
withdraw from the town and completed its withdrawal by mid-June.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong SLA, established in 1985, are trained and
financed by Israeli forces to help them patrol the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that another militiaman was wounded in a
separate bombing blast.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has
claimed responsibility for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 14 years, more than 100 SLA militiamen were
killed in Jezzine and about 400 others were wounded in the bombing
ambushes launched by Hezbollah who is spearheading a war to oust
Israeli forces and its allied SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
SLA commander Antoine Lahd Monday on Monday said Jezzine is
very dangerous for his 140-man garrison, whose commander has been
killed and his predecessor seriously wounded in Hezbollah's
earlier attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
