<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Wants Curb on Subsidized Pork Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Pork Industry
Board would lodge an application this week for a temporary
safeguard against subsidized pork being imported into the country
from Canada and Australia.
</P>
<P>
A Wellington-based newspaper Tuesday quoted Brian Milne, chief
executive of the Board, as saying that the application will be
lodged with the NZ Commerce Ministry in response to the serious
injury that subsidized imports are causing NZ port producers.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the unsubsidized New Zealand lamb exports to the United
States which is likely to impose restriction on them, he said, the
Canadian and Australian pork imports are heavily subsidized.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion also quoted Board Chairman Neil Managh as saying
that during the past year, pork imports, mainly from Canada and
Australia, have risen to 30 percent of NZ domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
This is forcing many NZ producers, especially the smaller
producers, out of business, he added.
</P>
<P>
Managh said the NZ government and Meat New Zealand, which are
fighting a battle with the United States over proposals to raise
tariffs on New Zealand and Australian lamb, have not said anything
 about the NZ safeguard action because "they are different
issues."
</P>
<P>
"Those farmers in Canada, America and Australia all have
subsidies, and we have figures to prove it," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
