<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Scientists Say Garlic Against Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Two New Zealand agricultural
scientists say people who eat as little as half a clove of raw
garlic a day may gain protection against bowel cancer, the New
Zealand Press Association (NZPA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Husband and wife research team Rex and Christine Munday, of
Hamilton, a city on New Zealand's North Island, are about to
publish a paper in the international journal Nutrition and Cancer
quantifying the beneficial effects of the "stinking rose," as
garlic is sometimes known.
</P>
<P>
Modern researchers have concentrated on garlic's perceived
ability to reduce the risk of disease, particularly
cardiovascular disease and intestinal bacterial infections. The
Mundays have studied its potential cancer-prevention properties,
in an effort to find out how much would need to be eaten for a
person to benefit, NZPA reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
