<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Daunting Tasks Lie Ahead for ANC (I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Millions of South Africans go
to the polls Wednesday to elect their second democratic government
which they think is best positioned to address their needs.
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress (ANC) will win the
election, and win it handsomely as opinion polls put it far ahead
of other much smaller contesting parties.
</P>
<P>
But will the ANC be able to live up to high expectations of
different classes in its second term in office?
</P>
<P>
Unlike in 1994 when the ANC won the first all-race election,
the new government will not have the luxury of basking in the
after-glow of a "miracle" transition. The new government's tasks
are enormous and the excuse of naivety is no longer available to
those who must perform the tasks.
</P>
<P>
The ANC has to fulfill its long-promised goals of free
education, free health care, affordable housing, job creation,
improved public transport and a responsible welfare system.
</P>
<P>
People's expectations differ according to one's political,
social and economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
For the capitalist class, the owners of property and
controllers of production, expectations and concerns include how
the election will affect their stake.
</P>
<P>
The petty bourgeoisie is also waiting in the wings to see if
these elections will open more opportunities for them.
</P>
<P>
The majority blacks want the ANC to ensure them of a decent
life which includes employment, basic education, health care and
adequate housing. "Black people first" -- an election call of the
Socialist Party of Azania -- demonstrates the urgency for the ANC
to address the basic needs of the black majority.
</P>
<P>
This is in fact a promise by the ANC when it took power after
the 1994 election. How long will it take for the ANC to live up
to its promises? This is a question constantly raised by ANC
supporters and opponents alike.
</P>
<P>
There is also a series of pressing issues the ANC must divert
its major attention to -- mounting corruption, rising crimes and
deteriorating unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Joblessness, which was cited as the number one priority of
South Africans in every single survey conducted since 1994, was
surely the Achilles heel of the ANC, which has introduced
legislation that has made it difficult for businesses to take on
new workers.
</P>
<P>
But this is ignored in favor of crime, with some of the parties
 lambasting the ANC for being soft on crimes because most
perpetrators were black.
</P>
<P>
The ANC abolished the capital punishment soon after it came to
power, a move that was blamed for rising crimes. ANC officials
have indicated time and again that the party has no intention to
reinstate capital punishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0243 </DOCNO>
