<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Daunting Tasks Lie Ahead for ANC (II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unemployment, which stands at about 30 percent, has worsened
poverty. Most workers earn below the bread line and live in
shanty houses. The new government has to build 300,000 new houses
to ease the housing shortage.
</P>
<P>
It is no accident that the country's education system is in
such a depressing state, with an official figure of 60,000
classrooms in shortage. The ANC has a long way to go before it
can fulfill its goal of free education.
</P>
<P>
To make South Africa more governable is another task for the
ANC. As complaints grow for low effectiveness and red tape, the
ANC has to take the first step to change the culture of government
from the top down.
</P>
<P>
Thabo Mbeki, ANC chairman and president-in-waiting, has chosen
to centralize control of his executives and impose his will
directly on ministers.
</P>
<P>
He has promised to make effective the main criteria in the
appointment of his cabinet ministers. ANC officials have also
indicated that the performance of ministers, once appointed, would
be constantly evaluated in the same way private sector companies
do their managers.
</P>
<P>
In addition to measures for improving government efficiency,
the ANC has outlined its policies to fulfill its tasks in the
fields of crime control, education, health, housing and job
creations:
</P>
<P>
-- Drastically reduce the number of guns in circulation and
introduce tougher gun controls and harsher sentences for serious
crimes;
</P>
<P>
-- Move as rapidly as possible to "free, dynamic and
compulsory" education and continue to ensure the fostering of a
culture of learning, teaching and service;
</P>
<P>
-- Develop a comprehensive, affordable and accessible national
public health system, financed in part by a social health
insurance program;
</P>
<P>
-- Seek an "honest agreement" with the private sector and work
with trade unions to channel investment into housing; and
</P>
<P>
-- Introduce labor-intensive investment throughout the economy,
as well as promote sectors that have large employment potential
like tourism, manufacturing, small and large-scale agriculture and
labor-intensive beneficialness of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Inherited from the first democratic government which made a
start with transformation, peace and sensible economic policies,
the next government has to get down to another five years of hard
work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
