<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Withdraw Export Quota for Garments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
decided to withdraw free export quota for garments from January 1,
2000 in order to eliminate its misuse by dishonest businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Secretary Alamgir Farruk Chowdhury said on Monday that
the ministry had already taken a decision to withdraw the free
quota to save the facility from being misused, The Independent
daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But it would not be implemented immediately until the beginning
of next year to allow enough time to review the decision, he said.
The ministry was now receiving requests from business quarters to
review the decision, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chowdhury said the free quota facility was introduced to help
new exporters, but the authorities had a bitter experience as free
quota holders, who by and large did not utilize the facility, sold
the papers to others in the market thereby giving rise to a big
black-market.
</P>
<P>
Raziur Rahman Raju, chairman of the Parliamentary Standing
Committee on the Commerce Ministry, said that the committee
reviewed the procedure for garment export quota allocation on
Sunday and felt that its administration should be tightened to
check loopholes.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to withdraw the free quota was quite justified in
view of its widespread misuse by exporters, he said. Some
businessmen were even showing documents of fake garments factories
and claiming allocation of free quota only to sell it in the open
market at a high price.
</P>
<P>
The government has also tightened the procedure for transfer of
other categories of quotas from passing more than one hand to curb
speculative business, the report quoted a source as saying.
</P>
<P>
As part of the verification mechanism, the Export Promotion
Bureau (EPB) would set up on-line computer network with importers
on the other side to check that quota documents were being
properly maintained by exporters here and nobody had tampered with
the documents to his advantage, he said.
</P>
<P>
A report in Tuesday's The Daily Star newspaper said 10 of the
country's garments manufacturers were discovered to export
apparels valued at 1.43 million U.S. dollars to the United States
recently by forging export visas and quota documents.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 and 1998, 72 forged export visas were detected by the
EPB, which had served notices against all of them, with the
operation of four of them suspended and four others penalized, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The garment industry, which has become the country's largest
foreign exchange earner, earned approximately 3.8 billion dollars
in the 1997-98 fiscal year ending on June 30, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
