<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Inflation Seen at 7.5 Percent By Dec. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson said Monday that he was expecting the country's
inflation rate to drop to 7.5 percent by December from 8 percent
in April.
</P>
<P>
The Malaya newspaper Tuesday quoted him as saying that the
inflation rate would average at 8-9 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the Central Bank's key overnight rates will again
be lowered after this week's respite if the May inflation rate
proves to be manageable.
</P>
<P>
Economists fear that the recent increase in the price of oil
might trigger another round of price hikes.
</P>
<P>
Singson told an economic forum that the financial crisis is
over for the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite pessimism that the country's economy
contracted in the first quarter, official figures showed it grew
by 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The gross national product (GNP) was better than the National
Economic Development Authority's projection of 0.8 percent growth
for the three-month period.
</P>
<P>
The market sentiment at present is more upbeat as the first
quarter economic results were better-than-expected, he said.
</P>
<P>
The stockmarket index has also risen to 2,400 since the
beginning of this year when it started from its lowest level ever
recorded at 1,192 points.
</P>
<P>
However, Singson cited several stumbling blocks to recovery,
including the ability of the high-flying U.S. economy to achieve a
soft landing and the ability of the Japanese economy to finally
turn around. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
