<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Deploy 45 Military Liaison Officers in E.Timor: Wiranto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations plans to deploy
45 military liaison officers in East Timor to help make the August
direct ballot on the U.N.-sponsored autonomy package a success,
Defense Minister/Armed Forces Chief Gen. Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
"They will not be armed and will be placed in the Indonesian
security forces' units in efforts to create a conducive situation
there," Wiranto said after attending a meeting of the Security
Restoration and Law Enforcement Council which was led by President
B.J. Habibie at the presidential office here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. military liaison officers would come from some neutral
countries, Wiranto was quoted by Antara News Agency Tuesday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
With their presence, he hoped there will be no manipulated or
biased reports on East Timor regarding the holding of the
U.N.-supervised popular consultation on the autonomy package.
</P>
<P>
The 45 U.N. military liaison officers in East Timor, as
proposed by Jakarta, would complement the 241 international
officers, 420 foreign volunteers, 280 U.N. civilian police
advisors and 4,000 Indonesian officials involved in the
organization and supervision of the upcoming popular consultation.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Indonesia and Portugal on May 5,
the U.N. will deploy civilian police advisers from several
countries to assist Indonesian police in maintaining law and
order. A key function will be the disarmament of rival factions
that are either for or against independence.
</P>
<P>
The August 8 ballot will allow the territory's people to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
In the direct vote, East Timorese aged 17 years or above have
the right to vote whether they accept the wide-ranging autonomy
package. If they reject it, the Indonesian government will
consider a separation of the province from the country's
territory.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Open-Air Market to Be Restored in Myanmar Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The five-decade-old famous Central
Open-Air Market in Myanmar's capital of Yangon, which was
demolished and demarcated for a hotel construction project, will
reopen following the failure of a South Korean company to
implement the project.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of the Myanmar Business magazine,
the land plot of the open air market, located in downtown Yangon
and opposite to the popular Bo Gyoke Aung San Market, was first
leased by the Idris Hydraulic Co. of Malaysia under a contract
with Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian company later handed the land lot to the Daewoo
Corporation of South Korea for building a hotel, the magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
As Daewoo could not implement the project, the previous
open-air market will be allowed to resume business as before, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has been placing emphasis on building hotels as part of
its efforts to promote tourism since it opened to foreign
investment in late 1988, adopting a market-oriented economic
system.
</P>
<P>
However, the occupancy rate of hotels has been unfavorable over
the past few years and a number of foreign-invested hotel projects
have been suspended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
