<HEADLINE> 139 Registered Groups to Monitor Indonesian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The General Election Commission
(KPU) has registered 139 organizations to participate in
monitoring activities for the June 7 general election in
Indonesia, The Indonesian Observer reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The registration for election monitoring agencies began on May
12 and ended on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to KPU officials, the real number of monitoring
groups is much higher than 139.
</P>
<P>
"The final number doesn't include those who directly registered
with the Regional General Election Committees throughout the
country," said KPU official Untoro Rudiyanto, who led the
registration procedures.
</P>
<P>
About 20 foreign non-governmental organizations (NGOs) with a
total of 515 personnel will monitor the polls. At least 119
domestic NGOs with about 3,500 personnel are also to observe the
election.
</P>
<P>
The Carter Center, an organization led by former U.S. President
Jimmy Carter, has 109 personnel to take part in election
monitoring activities.
</P>
<P>
About 139 foreign diplomats from 13 countries will also be
involved in the monitoring. Most are from Australia, the United
States, New Zealand, Japan, the Philippines, Canada, France,
Sweden and Norway. 
</P>
