<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's International Airport to Be Expanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Bandaranaike
International Airport is to be expanded and modernized with the
construction of a boarding bridge, a new duty-free shopping
complex and a passenger terminal, official sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The program, which will cost 100 million U.S. dollars, is to be
funded by the Japan Overseas Economic Development Cooperation
Fund.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation
said priority will be given to the boarding bridge which will
expedite boarding.
</P>
<P>
The program also includes the construction of a runway and the
expansion of the cargo section, which will be funded by the Sri
Lankan government, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new duty-free complex is to ease congestion when there are
heavy arrivals. An additional baggage belt will also be
constructed.
</P>
<P>
The Bandaranaike International Airport was originally an air
base of the Royal Air Force during World War II. In 1956, it was
handed over to the Ceylon Air Force.
</P>
<P>
In 1963 it was converted into a civil airport and later named
the Bandaranaike International Airport in memory of the Late prime
minister S.W.R.D. Bandaranaike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
