<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Under GSP Tumble 18 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports of goods under
the GSP tax privilege program in 1998 fell by 18.69 percent to
8.54 billion U.S. dollars, according to the Foreign Trade
Department of the Thai Commerce ministry.
</P>
<P>
A report released by the department available Tuesday said
Thailand's exports under the GSP program dropped from 10.51
billion U.S. dollars in 1997 to 8.54 billion U.S. dollars in 1998.
Of the total, agriculture goods accounted for 1.81 billion U.S.
dollars and the rest for industrial goods.
</P>
<P>
The EU ranked first and granted tax privileges to Thailand
worth 3.8 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 compared to 5.48 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997. The United States ranked second, granting
2.69 billion U.S. dollars, up from 2.52 billion U.S. dollars in
1997, followed by Japan, 1.47 billion U.S. dollars, a fall from
1.86 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The top five product groups for which GSP privileges were
sought included computer parts (34.49 million U.S. dollars),
processed shrimp (302.61 million U.S. dollars), vans and pick-up
truck weighting not over five tons (240.77 million U.S. dollars),
frozen shrimp (222.29 million U.S. dollars) and input-output units
(198.29 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
