<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: East Asia Expected to See Export Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- After significant declines for three
consecutive years, East Asia's exports as a whole are expected to
pick up this year as signs of growth have already emerged in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the cyclical changes in the world electronic market
and weak global consumption demand had led to a slowdown of export
growth in East Asia. Even the 20-80 percent currency devaluation
in some East Asian countries had failed to prompt an export rise
in the 1997-98 period.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation has been changing recently. According to
official figures, the Philippines registered a 15-percent export
growth in the first quarter of this year. Singapore's non-oil
exports grew by 8.5 percent in April. The rise broke a six-month
declining trend.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, although export revenues declined in the first
quarter year on year, it rose by 2.5 percent in April. South
Korea's export also grew by 1.5 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
While East Asia has not seen remarkable export growth yet, the
prospects are brighter than last year. One reason for optimism is
that Japan's imports from East Asia began to grow again after a
year of decline.
</P>
<P>
Japan's imports from Asia rose in February for the first time
in 14 months with imports from Singapore rising by 2.7 percent and
that from China by 19.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In April, Japan's imports from Asian nations went up 1.2
percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
"A recovery in Asian nations would mean that Japan's imports
and exports with them will be boosted because of the close
economic linkage," said Masaaki Suzuki, an economist at Fuji
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
As East Asian countries' major export destination, growing
imports by Japan would inevitably stimulate export growth in the
region, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
As well, the rising imports by East Asian countries have
brightened the hope for export growth in the region, where about
40 percent of trade activities are conducted among East Asian
countries themselves.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Philippines' imports fell 18 percent due to an
economic recession. But with the economic recovery in place, the
country's imports increased by 1.5 percent in March from a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, imports grew 9.4 percent year on year in April,
boosted by rising demand.
</P>
<P>
But the most encouraging news for East Asian countries is the
higher demand for semiconductors and other electronic products in
Japan, Europe and the United States, because electronics dominate
export products of the region.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, semiconductor imports grew 14 percent in April and
the United States and European countries are also purchasing more
electronic products from East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the higher demand promoted electronics exports in
the region. In Singapore, where 70 percent non-oil export products
are electronics, export of electronic products increased 14
percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, whose 50 percent of export revenues are
from electronics, exports of electronics products grew by 15
percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the stronger regional currencies and Japan's
economic recession will still have a negative impact on East
Asia's export and the growth will, therefore, be modest this year,
analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
