<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs Edge out Trail Blazers 86-85 to Go to 2-0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Sean Elliott's improbable
balancing act somehow toppled the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
Elliot tiptoed along the sideline and sank his sixth 3-pointer
with 9.9 seconds left, giving the San Antonio Spurs a remarkable
86-85 victory over the Trail Blazers and a 2-0 lead in the Western
Conference finals in San Antonio today.
</P>
<P>
With the Spurs trailing by two points, Elliott took an in-
bounds pass along the right sideline. He nearly fell out of bounds
and dribbled once before keeping his heels off the sideline and
launching a 3-pointer over the outstretched arm of Rasheed Wallace.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know how I did it," Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
The shot brought the Spurs all the way back from an 18-point
second-half deficit and gave them their first lead of the game.
They made it stand up as Jimmy Jackson had a shot blocked and Walt
Williams missed a banker before time expired.
</P>
<P>
Elliott scored 22 points, making 6-of-7 three-pointers. He was
the only player making any outside shots for the Spurs, who barely
escaped with their eighth straight play-off win and home-court
advantage intact.
</P>
<P>
It was a crushing loss for the Trail Blazers, who led by eight
points with less than two minutes to go. In four games at the
Alamodome this season, Portland has lost by four points, twice by
one point and in overtime.
</P>
<P>
Game 3 is on Friday at Portland. The Blazers are faced with
having to beat the Spurs four times in the next five games, a tall
order considering San Antonio has lost four times in its last 32
games.
</P>
<P>
Tim Duncan had 23 points, 10 rebounds and five blocks and David
Robinson added 14, seven rebounds for the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
Damon Stoudamire had 15 points and seven assists for Portland.
Arvydas Sabonis led Portland with 17 points but did not play in
the fourth quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
