<HEADLINE> 2,700-Year Old Tombs Found in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have found
300 ancient tombs dating back to the Eastern Zhou Dynasty (770-256
B.C.) in Xiaochang County, central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The tombs cover an area of 5.3 square kilometers and their
location is just 300 meters away from Caodianfang, a city ruins of
the same historical period.
</P>
<P>
An archaeologist said that the tomb area is undoubtedly the
graveyard for the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
"The tombs have three chamber patterns: oblong, square and
echelon," the expert said, adding that more than 2,000 pieces of
cultural relics have been unearthed, including pottery cooking
vessels and containers such as kettles, jars and cups as well as
bronze weapons such as swords, daggers and arrowheads.
</P>
<P>
"The discovery will provide valuable clues for the study of
cultural development in the area," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
