<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Enhance Industrial Productivity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is making efforts to enhance
industrial productivity by taking measures to improve the quality
of products and reduce production cost, a government minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Measures are being taken to introduce modern techniques,
machines and management systems and to utilize raw materials and
equipment in the most effective way, said Myanmar Minister of
Science and Technology U Thaung, who is also chairman of the
Myanmar Industrial Development Committee.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar here on Sunday on the enhancement of
productivity of the Hlinetharya Industrial Zone in Yangon, U
Thaung said various departments under his ministry will render
assistance in research work to carry out standardization, quality
control and production management tasks to help promote
productivity.
</P>
<P>
He said Asian countries have been working to enhance
productivity in the past 40 years and there are now 18 members in
the Asia Productivity Organization (APO) which is based in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar attended a recent APO meeting as a special guest.
</P>
<P>
He said that not only the industrial sector but also the
agricultural, fish and meat, mining and other sectors should be
promoted for national economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He called for coordination and cooperation among government
departments, cooperatives and private industrialists for the
enhancement of productivity.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's industrial sector
grew by 5.3 percent in output value in 1997-98, accounting for 9.2
percent of the GDP and becoming the second largest contributor to
the GDP after agriculture. The figures for 1998-99 are not
available.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which began on Sunday and ends on Thursday, is
being attended by officials of government departments and over 50
representatives of the Hlinetharya Industrial Zone, the most
successful one out of the six of its kind in Yangon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
