<HEADLINE> Philippine Companies to Be Fined for Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 4,000 Philippine firms will
be fined 50,000 pesos (1,250 U.S. dollars) each by the country's
Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) for failure to submit
their year 2000 Compliance questionnaires in December last year.
</P>
<P>
SEC said in a recently released memorandum that as of December
29, 1998, 3,943 companies had failed to comply with the
requirement to submit a duly accomplished Year 2000 Compliance
questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the penalty, SEC said companies will also be paying
for each day that they failed to submit after the December 29
deadline.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the SEC formed a Y2K task force that will be
responsible for the monitoring of the Y2K compliance of registered
firms.
</P>
<P>
The task force made a survey through questionnaires which aims
to assess the companies in three categories - their business
vulnerability, Y2K resource and Y2K plan.
</P>
<P>
SEC reported that out of the 1,040 questionnaires submitted,
667 companies said they do not depend on computerized systems
while only 81 firms said they are highly reliable on computerized
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
