<HEADLINE> Central America Recuperates from Hurricane "Mitch" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, May 31 (Xinhua)-- Central America has recuperated
25 percent from the devastation which hurricane "Mitch" inflicted
upon it last year, vice president of the Commission of Social
Affairs of the Central American Parliament (Parlacen) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The vice president, Aniano Pinzon, said that up to now,
countries affected by the meteorological phenomenon have received
from abroad over one billion U.S. dollars in humanitarian help and
long term loans.
</P>
<P>
European and South American countries, the People's Republic of
China and the United States sent food assistance and large
quantity of medicines, and condoned the country's external debts,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The countries most affected by the atmospheric phenomenon were
Honduras and Nicaragua, where over 80 percent of the productive
infrastructure was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
"Although the rehabilitation of the main ways of communication
and some producing centers of these two countries has been
achieved, there's still a lot left to be done," said Pinzon.
</P>
</TEXT>
