<HEADLINE> Chemical Sector Seeking Foreign Cooperation for Clean Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China's chemical industry is
seeking intensified cooperation with foreign companies to
introduce advanced clean production techniques and expertise as
well as approaches to treat pollution, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to working with foreign companies to bring
advanced production expertise, waste treatment technologies and
capital to China," Lin Yincai, secretary-general of China
Association for Chemical Pollution Prevention for Chemical
Pollution Prevention and Control Technology (CACPPCT) was quoted
by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, China has made remarkable progress
in solving pollution problems in the chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
As many as 554 environmental protection supervisory stations
have been established across the nation, with more than 20,000
staff members engaged in the sector.
</P>
<P>
However, the chemical industry now produces about five billion
tons of waste water, 850 billion cubic meters of airborne
emissions and 46 million tons of solid waste each year.
</P>
<P>
Over the next five years, China will enhance pollution control
in the chemical sector by stressing measures taken in the
production process. Massive technical upgrading will be carried
out. Comprehensive utilization of resources is also encouraged,
according to the State Petrochemical Industry Bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
