<HEADLINE> Chinese Forestry Officials Urged to Fight Tree Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A deadly tree disease - poplar
canker is sweeping across north and northeast China, destroying
green areas in several cities.
</P>
<P>
The State Forestry Administration (SFA) has urged local
forestry bureaus to take emergency measures to monitor and combat
the disease.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic is caused by bacteria-carrying parasites in the
trees, SFA officials noted in an urgent circular issued over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The bacteria has destroyed approximately 30,000 trees - causing
withering and rotting of their bark - in Shenyang City, capital of
Liaoning Province, Harbin City, capital of Heilongjiang Province
and Tianjin Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The disease has been detected in Changchun, Dalian, Anshan and
Qinhuangdao in Jilin, Liaoning and Hebei provinces, administration
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic's outbreak was "unprecedented and unexpected," and
may have been caused, in part, by weather conditions,
administration officials suggested.
</P>
<P>
"Last winter's drought reduced the water in the trees, which
weakened their ability to fight bacteria," noted Wang Xiaohua,
division director of the administration's Anti-Pest and Disease
Center.
</P>
<P>
"Another reason is the spring's humidity was good for the
growth of the bacteria," Wang added.
</P>
<P>
Forestry officials were ordered to remove the decayed and
contaminated trees to prevent further infestation, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The administration is recommending tree-friendly chemical
pesticides be used to kill the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Forestry officials were also urged to establish monitoring
centers and undertake measures to stop infestation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
