<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers Vice-chairman Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Scotland's Rangers football club
vice-chairman Donald Findlay has resigned over reports of
sectarianism.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Monday, the vice-chairman sang
anti-Roman Catholic songs after his club's 1-0 win over Celtic in
the Scottish Cup Final.
</P>
<P>
The 48-year-old is reported to have broken into song at an
after-match party at the club's Ibrox ground on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mr Findlay, a QC and one of Scotland's leading lawyers, sang
The Sash and Follow, Follow, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
In his resignation letter, Mr Findlay describes the incident as
"a serious misjudgment".
</P>
<P>
He says his conduct "was not acceptable" and he regrets any
harm done to the club's reputation.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have recently been made by both Old Firm clubs to
diffuse religious tension between supporters, particularly in the
light of a violent game on May 2, where the referee needed
stitches after being struck by a coin.
</P>
<P>
A massive police operation was under way on Saturday when the
game itself passed off peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Later that night a 20-year-old Celtic fan was hit in the chest
by a crossbow bolt outside a Glasgow pub while another was later
attacked in a take-away. 
</P>
