<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, June 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- A total of 25,000 South Africans die of tobacco-
related illnesses every year, the Health Department said Monday,
the World No-Tobacco Day.
</P>
<P>
The department said in a statement that smokers lose an average
of 12 years of their lives in South Africa. (SAfrica-Smoking-
Death)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- The Zanzibar Island, one of the leading
tourist attractions in east Africa, has been experiencing power
blackout for two days.
</P>
<P>
Engineers in Zanzibar said Monday that the outage is a result
of technical fault at the main transformer at Mtoni which receives
electricity from the mainland of Tanzania through a submarine
cable. (Zanzibar-Power Blackout)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- The New National Party (NNP) has ruled out a
coalition with the African National Congress (ANC) in the Western
Cape after South Africa's general election on June 2.
</P>
<P>
Should there be a coalition, the first choice of the NNP would
be one or more of the other opposition parties, South African
Press Association (SAPA) quoted NNP leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk
as saying in Cape Town Monday.
</P>
<P>
The NNP leader said his party is going "full-out" to win the
province on its own. (SAfrica-Party Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Scientists working in the University of Hawaii, the
United States, said on Monday they have cloned the first live male
mouse from adult cells.
</P>
<P>
The male mouse, nicknamed "Fibro", which is short for
fibroblast, the type of cell from which he was derived, was cloned
using tail-tip cells of adult male mice.
</P>
<P>
Cloning entire animals from adult cells has recently been
accomplished in sheep, mice and cows. (Clone-Male Mouse)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Sales of chicken and eggs produced in Belgium may
be prohibited by the European Union (EU) after stocks of some
farms were found to contain high levels of cancer-causing chemical
dioxin, an EU official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
EU experts on animal feed meet on Monday and Tuesday to
determine what a further step should be taken to curb the food
health scare. Belgium's health ministry banned domestic sales last
Friday of chicken and eggs, saying the move was a precaution
pending the results of further tests due this week.  (Belgium-
Chicken-Ban)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema Monday
reaffirmed that that NATO's raids on Yugoslavia should be
suspended once a United Nations resolution on Kosovo is secured.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his regular Monday briefing, D'Alema said that if a
UN Security Council resolution is agreed, "it will be necessary to
suspend the bombings." (Italy-Yugoslavia) 
</P>
