<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Airlifts Military Personnel, Equipment to Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 31 (Xinhua) -- NATO transport planes sent a
batch of military personnel and equipment to Romania on Sunday to
facilitate NATO's bombing campaign in Yugoslavia via Romanian
airspace, Romanian Defense Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that two NATO C-130 Hercules
transport planes carrying a 100-man military team and war
materials arrived at the Craiova civil airport, over 100 kilograms
from the Romania-Yugoslavia border.
</P>
<P>
Jessus Flores, head of the NATO military team, revealed on
Monday his people will complete the installation and testing of a
mobile radar within the next few days to ensure normal air traffic
near the Romania-Yugoslavia border.
</P>
<P>
Romania, which is seeking an early entry into NATO, made a
positive response to the alliance's request for the country to
open its sky "unconditionally" to NATO war planes.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Defense Minister Victor Babiuc said his country would
allow NATO to use its four airports near the Romania-Yugoslavia
border, including the Craiova airport, if NATO makes such requests.
</P>
</TEXT>
