<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium May Face Chicken-Egg Ban, EU Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Sales of chicken and eggs produced
in Belgium may be prohibited by the European Union (EU) after
stocks of some farms were found to contain high levels of
cancer-causing chemical dioxin, an EU official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
EU experts on animal feed meet on Monday and Tuesday to
determine what a further step should be taken to curb the food
health scare. Belgium's health ministry banned domestic sales last
Friday of chicken and eggs, saying the move was a precaution
pending the results of further tests due this week.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner Franz Fischler may propose a ban that
could be cleared as early as Tuesday, the official said. EU member
states have an obligation to ensure that products placed on the
market are safe, and "what we do depend on where the Belgian
authorities are in terms of handling the problem," he added.
</P>
<P>
An EU ban could apply throughout the bloc's 15 member countries
or worldwide. "A ban could be selective or global, depending on
whether the problem is universal or only linked to a limited
number of farms," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's agriculture ministry said it was investigating high
dioxin levels in chicken meat and eggs linked to a batch of animal
feed contaminated with dioxin. Currently, such dioxin is related
to a kind of oil in chicken feed. Dioxin is a highly toxic
chemical which, once absorbed into the human body, is not excreted
and can cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
The EU official said the European Commission would decide
whether to make a proposal for a ban after hearing evidence from
the Belgian authorities. Any proposal could be voted on by the
EU's top veterinary committee, which meets on Tuesday and
Wednesday. The European Commission, EU's executive branch, could
put such a ban into law as soon as possible If 15 governments of
the EU were to back the move.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
