<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy PM Urges End of Raids on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
Monday reaffirmed that that NATO's raids on Yugoslavia should be
suspended once a United Nations resolution on Kosovo is secured.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his regular Monday briefing, D'Alema said that if a
UN Security Council resolution is agreed, "it will be necessary to
suspend the bombings."
</P>
<P>
He also voiced renewed concern over the civilian victims of the
bombings and expressed support for a European defense structure
within the NATO framework, as proposed by France and Germany at
the last weekend.
</P>
<P>
He said Italy supported a French and German proposal to
establish a European security and defense structure within NATO
and is prepared to contribute to the plan.
</P>
<P>
He said the structure would not be "separate" from NATO but
"separable" and with its own operational independence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
