<DOCNO> XIE19990601.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Clone First Male Mouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Scientists working in the University
of Hawaii, the United States, said on Monday they have cloned the
first live male mouse from adult cells.
</P>
<P>
The male mouse, nicknamed "Fibro", which is short for
fibroblast, the type of cell from which he was derived, was cloned
using tail-tip cells of adult male mice.
</P>
<P>
Cloning entire animals from adult cells has recently been
accomplished in sheep, mice and cows.
</P>
<P>
However, previously reported clones have all been produced
using adult cells related to the female reproductive system, which
raised the question of whether male mammals can be cloned in this
way.
</P>
<P>
The birth of Fibro demonstrated that cloning using adult cells
is not restricted to female or reproductive cells at all, said the
researchers, Teruhiko Wakayama and Ryuzo Yanagimachi.
</P>
<P>
The results suggested that it should be possible to store the
complete genome of mouse in the form of adult cells such as tail
tip, rather than embryos, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, precious animals of either sex, for example
endangered species and transgenic animals, can be propagated by
cloning irrespective of their fertility status," they wrote in the
journal Nature Genetics.
</P>
<P>
To produce Fibro, the scientists, who cloned the first mouse
from the female "cumulus" cells in 1997, used cells isolated from
male mice's tail-tips freed from skin.
</P>
<P>
The nucleus of the donor male cells were injected into an
enucleated oocyte to develop into embryos, which were then
implanted into surrogate mother mice.
</P>
<P>
"Only three of 274 transferred embryos reached full term," the
researchers reported, "three mice from tail-tip cells were born
alive, all of them males with black eyes."
</P>
<P>
The weights of the three offspring were within the range for
normal newborn mice at the time of birth. Among them, two died
within one hour after caesarian section due to respiratory
failure.
</P>
<P>
The remaining male pup, Fibro, has developed into a fertile
adult male mouse with the same color as the tail-tip cell donor.
</P>
<P>
Fibro now is completely normal in all respects, including body
weight, growth and fertility, the researchers reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
